# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gasoline
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gasoline/1-2-4-trimethylbenzene] In 1849, Charles Blachford Mansfield rectified coal tar and identified fractions which he hypothesized to be cumole and cymole.
[src:gasoline/1-2-4-trimethylbenzene] The latter fraction boiled slightly above 170 °C (338 °F) and had specific density of 0.857.
[src:gasoline/1-2-4-trimethylbenzene] In 1862, Warren De la Rue and Hugo Müller (1833-1915) proposed the term **pseudocumole** for the fractions heavier than xylole.
[src:gasoline/1-2-4-trimethylbenzene] When three years later American chemist Cyrus Warren (1824-1891) attempted to reproduce Mansfield's results, he determined that the oil boiling at 170 °C (338 °F) has the same formula as cumole, not cymole, and suggested to name it **isocumole**.
[src:gasoline/1-2-4-trimethylbenzene] The structure of the compound was determined by Th.
[src:gasoline/1-2-4-trimethylbenzene] Ernst and Wilhelm Rudolph Fittig, who first prepared it from bromoxylene and iodomethane in 1866 by a Wurtz–Fittig reaction developed two years earlier.
[src:gasoline/1-2-4-trimethylbenzene] In the next year, Fittig et al. adopted the pseudocumol terminology, in 1869 Fittig and B.
[src:gasoline/1-2-4-trimethylbenzene] Wackenroder proved that the fraction is a mixture of mesitylene with another trimethylbenzene, for which the name of pseudocumol was retained, and in 1886 Oscar Jacobsen showed that the third trimethylbenzene he discovered earlier is also present.
[src:gasoline/1-2-4-trimethylbenzene] Industrially, it is isolated from the C9 aromatic hydrocarbon fraction during petroleum distillation.
[src:gasoline/1-2-4-trimethylbenzene] Approximately 40% of this fraction is 1,2,4-trimethylbenzene.
[src:gasoline/1-2-4-trimethylbenzene] It is also generated by methylation of toluene and xylenes and the disproportionation of xylene over aluminosilicate catalysts.
[src:gasoline/1-2-4-trimethylbenzene] Pseudocumene is a precursor to trimellitic anhydride, from which high performance polymers are made.
[src:gasoline/1-2-4-trimethylbenzene] It is also used as a sterilizing agent and in the making of dyes, perfumes and resins.
[src:gasoline/1-2-4-trimethylbenzene] Another use is as an antiknock agent, since its research and motor octane numbers are well above 100.
[src:gasoline/1-2-4-trimethylbenzene] In automobile fuel it is a minor additive, with its share in US gasoline rising from 0.03%–0.5% in early 1990s to 1.1%–2.6% in 2011.
[src:gasoline/1-2-4-trimethylbenzene] It may be a major component of some avgas formulations.
[src:gasoline/1-2-4-trimethylbenzene] 1,2,4-Trimethylbenzene dissolved in mineral oil is used as a liquid scintillator in particle physics experiments such as NOνA and Borexino.
[src:gasoline/1-2-dibromoethane] Historically, 1,2-dibromoethane was used as a component in anti-knock additives in leaded fuels.
[src:gasoline/1-2-dibromoethane] It reacts with lead residues to generate volatile lead bromides, thereby preventing fouling of the engine with lead deposits.
[src:gasoline/1-2-dibromoethane] It has been used as a pesticide in soil and on various crops.
[src:gasoline/1-2-dibromoethane] The applications were initiated after the forced retirement of 1,2-dibromo-3-chloropropane (DBCP).
[src:gasoline/1-2-dibromoethane] Most of these uses have been stopped in the U.S.
[src:gasoline/1-2-dibromoethane] It continues to be used as a fumigant for treatment of logs for termites and beetles, and for control of moths in beehives.
[src:gasoline/1-2-dibromoethane] 1,2-Dibromoethane has wider applications in the preparation of other organic compounds including those carrying modified diazocine rings and vinyl bromide that is a precursor to some fire retardants.
[src:gasoline/1-2-dibromoethane] In organic synthesis, 1,2-dibromoethane is used to brominate carbanions and to activate magnesium for certain Grignard reagents.
[src:gasoline/1-2-dibromoethane] In the latter process, 1,2-dibromoethane reacts with magnesium, producing ethylene and magnesium bromide, which are innocuous, exposing a more active portion of the magnesium particle to the substrate.
[src:gasoline/1-2-dibromoethane] 1,2-Dibromoethane causes changes in the metabolism and severe destruction of living tissues.
[src:gasoline/1-2-dibromoethane] The known empirical LD50 values for 1,2-dibromoethane are 140 mg kg−1 (oral, rat), and 300.0 mg kg−1 (dermal, rabbit).
[src:gasoline/1-2-dibromoethane] 1,2-Dibromoethane is a known carcinogen, with pre-1977 exposure levels ranking it as the most carcinogenic substance on the HERP Index.
[src:gasoline/1-2-dibromoethane] The effects on people of breathing high levels are not known, but animal studies with short-term exposures to high levels caused depression and collapse, indicating effects on the brain.
[src:gasoline/1-2-dibromoethane] Changes in the brain and behavior were also seen in young rats whose male parents had breathed 1,2-dibromoethane, and birth defects were observed in the young of animals that were exposed while pregnant.
[src:gasoline/1-2-dibromoethane] 1,2-Dibromoethane is not known to cause birth defects in humans.
[src:gasoline/1-2-dibromoethane] Swallowing has caused death at 40ml doses.
[src:gasoline/1-2-dichloroethane] The chemical compound **1,2-dichloroethane**, commonly known as **ethylene dichloride** (**EDC**), is a chlorinated hydrocarbon.
[src:gasoline/1-2-dichloroethane] It is a colourless liquid with a chloroform-like odour.
[src:gasoline/1-2-dichloroethane] The most common use of 1,2-dichloroethane is in the production of vinyl chloride, which is used to make polyvinyl chloride (PVC) pipes, furniture and automobile upholstery, wall coverings, housewares, and automobile parts.
[src:gasoline/1-2-dichloroethane] 1,2-Dichloroethane is also used generally as an intermediate for other organic chemical compounds, and as a solvent.
[src:gasoline/1-2-dichloroethane] It forms azeotropes with many other solvents, including water (at a boiling point of 70.5 °C or 158.9 °F or 343.6 K) and other chlorocarbons.
[src:gasoline/1-2-dichloroethane] Although the *Gezelschap* in practice did not do much in-depth scientific research, they and their publications were highly regarded.
[src:gasoline/1-2-dichloroethane] Part of that acknowledgement is that 1,2-dichloroethane was called "Dutch oil" in old chemistry.
[src:gasoline/1-2-dichloroethane] This is also the origin of the archaic term "olefiant gas" (oil-making gas) for ethylene, for in this reaction it is ethylene that makes the Dutch oil.
[src:gasoline/1-2-dichloroethane] "Olefiant gas" is the etymological origin of the modern term "olefins", the family of hydrocarbons of which ethylene is the first member.
[src:gasoline/1-2-dichloroethane] Nearly 20 million tons of 1,2-dichloroethane are produced annually in the United States, Western Europe, and Japan.
[src:gasoline/1-2-dichloroethane] Approximately 95% of the world's production of 1,2-dichloroethane is used in the production of vinyl chloride monomer (VCM) with hydrogen chloride as a byproduct.
[src:gasoline/1-2-dichloroethane] VCM is the precursor to polyvinyl chloride.
[src:gasoline/1-2-dichloroethane] The hydrogen chloride can be re-used in the production of more 1,2-dichloroethane via the oxychlorination route described above.
[src:gasoline/1-2-dichloroethane] 1,2-Dichloroethane has been used as degreaser and paint remover but this use has phased out due to its toxicity.
[src:gasoline/1-2-dichloroethane] As a useful 'building block' reagent, it is used as an intermediate in the production of diverse organic compounds such as ethylenediamine and higher ethyleneamines.
[src:gasoline/1-2-dichloroethane] In the laboratory it is occasionally used as a source of chlorine, with elimination of ethene and chloride.
[src:gasoline/1-2-dichloroethane] Via several steps, 1,2-dichloroethane is a precursor to 1,1,1-trichloroethane.
[src:gasoline/1-2-dichloroethane] Historically, before leaded petrol was phased out, chloroethanes were used as an additive in petrol to prevent lead buildup in engines.
[src:gasoline/1-2-dichloroethane] It is also toxic (especially by inhalation due to its high vapour pressure) and possibly carcinogenic.
[src:gasoline/1-2-dichloroethane] Its high solubility and 50-year half-life in anoxic aquifers make it a perennial pollutant and health risk that is very expensive to treat conventionally, requiring a method of bioremediation.
[src:gasoline/1-2-dichloroethane] While the chemical is not used in consumer products manufactured in the U.S., a case was reported in 2009 of molded plastic consumer products (toys and holiday decorations) from China that released 1,2-dichloroethane into homes at levels high enough to produce cancer risk.
[src:gasoline/1-2-dichloroethane] Substitutes are recommended and will vary according to application.
[src:gasoline/1-2-dichloroethane] Dioxolane and toluene are possible substitutes as solvents.
[src:gasoline/1-2-dichloroethane] Dichloroethane is unstable in the presence of aluminium and, when moist, with zinc and iron.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Kerosene-based jet fuel is formulated to suit the requirements of turbine engines which have no octane requirement and operate over a much wider flight envelope than piston engines.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Kerosene is also used by most diesel piston engines developed for aviation use, such as those by SMA Engines, Austro Engine, and Thielert.
[src:gasoline/100ll] The main petroleum component used in blending avgas is alkylate, which is a mixture of various isooctanes.
[src:gasoline/100ll] All grades of avgas that meet CAN 2–3, 25-M82 have a density of 6.01 pounds per US gallon (720 g/L) at 15 °C (59 °F).
[src:gasoline/100ll] (6 lb/U.S. gal is commonly used in America for weight and balance computation.) Density increases to 6.41 pounds per US gallon (768 g/L) at −40 °C (−40 °F), and decreases by about 0.1% per 1 °C (1.8 °F) increase in temperature.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Avgas has an emission coefficient (or factor) of 18.355 pounds per US gallon (2.1994 kg/L) of CO2 or about 3.07 units of weight CO2 produced per unit weight of fuel used.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Avgas is less volatile, with a Reid vapor pressure range of 5.5 to 7 psi, than automotive gasoline, with a range of 8 to 14 psi.
[src:gasoline/100ll] A minimum limit ensures adequate volatility for engine starting.
[src:gasoline/100ll] The upper limits are related to atmospheric pressure at sea level, 14.7 psi, for motor vehicles and ambient pressure at 22,000 ft, 6.25 psi, for aircraft.
[src:gasoline/100ll] The lower avgas volatility reduces the chance of vapor lock in fuel lines at altitudes up to 22,000 ft.
[src:gasoline/100ll] The high octane ratings were traditionally achieved by the addition of tetraethyllead, a highly toxic substance that was phased out of automotive use in most countries in the late 20th century.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Historically, many post-WWII developed, low-powered 4- and 6-cylinder piston aircraft engines were designed to use leaded fuels; an unleaded replacement fuel is being developed and certified for these engines.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Some reciprocating-engine aircraft still require leaded fuels, but some do not, and some can burn unleaded gasoline if a special oil additive is used.
[src:gasoline/100ll] The annual US usage of avgas was 186 million US gallons (700,000 m3) in 2008, and was approximately 0.14% of the motor gasoline consumption.
[src:gasoline/100ll] From 1983 through 2008, US usage of avgas declined consistently by approximately 7.5 million US gallons (28,000 m3) each year.
[src:gasoline/100ll] As of 2024, the annual US usage of avgas was 180 million US gallons (680,000 m3), most of which contained lead, and 170,000 aircraft in the US used leaded avgas.
[src:gasoline/100ll] In Europe, avgas remains the most common piston-engine fuel.
[src:gasoline/100ll] High prices have encouraged efforts to convert to diesel engines burning jet fuel, which is more readily available, less expensive, and has advantages for aviation use.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Grades of avgas are identified by two numbers associated with its Motor Octane Number (MON).
[src:gasoline/100ll] The first number indicates the octane rating of the fuel tested to "aviation lean" standards, which is similar to the anti-knock index or "pump rating" given to automotive gasoline in the US.
[src:gasoline/100ll] The second number indicates the octane rating of the fuel tested to the "aviation rich" standard, which tries to simulate a supercharged condition with a rich mixture, elevated temperatures, and a high manifold pressure.
[src:gasoline/100ll] For example, **100/130** avgas has an octane rating of 100 at the lean settings usually used for cruising and 130 at the rich settings used for take-off and other full-power conditions.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Antiknock agents such as tetraethyl lead (TEL) help to control detonation and provide lubrication.
[src:gasoline/100ll] One gram of TEL contains 640.6 milligrams of lead.
[src:gasoline/100ll] 100LL (pronounced "one hundred low lead") may contain a maximum of one-half the tetraethyllead allowed in 100/130 (green) avgas.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Some of the lower-powered (100–150 horsepower or 75–112 kilowatts) aviation engines that were developed in the late 1990s are designed to run on unleaded fuel and on 100LL, an example being the Rotax 912.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Automotive gasoline—known as mogas or autogas among aviators—that does not contain ethanol may be used in certified aircraft that have a Supplemental Type Certificate (STC) for automotive gasoline, as well as in experimental aircraft and ultralight aircraft.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Some oxygenates other than ethanol are approved, but these STC's prohibit ethanol-laced gasolines.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Ethanol-treated gasoline is susceptible to phase-separation which is very possible due to the altitude/temperature changes light airplanes undergo in ordinary flight.
[src:gasoline/100ll] This ethanol-treated fuel can flood the fuel system with water which can cause in-flight engine failure.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Additionally, the phase-separated fuel can leave remaining portions that do not meet octane requirements due to the loss of the ethanol in the water-absorption process.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Further, the ethanol can attack materials in aircraft construction which pre-date "gasohol" fuels.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Most of these applicable aircraft have low-compression engines which were originally certified to run on 80/87 avgas and require only "regular" 87 anti-knock index automotive gasoline.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Examples include the popular Cessna 172 Skyhawk or Piper Cherokee with the 150 hp (110 kW) variant of the Lycoming O-320.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Some aircraft engines were originally certified using a 91/96 avgas and have STC's available to run "premium" 91 anti-knock index (AKI) automotive gasoline.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Examples include some Cherokees with the 160 hp (120 kW) Lycoming O-320 or 180 hp (130 kW) O-360, or the Cessna 152 with the O-235.
[src:gasoline/100ll] The AKI rating of typical automotive fuel might not directly correspond to the 91/96 avgas used to certify engines, as motor vehicle pumps in the US use the so-called "(R + M)/2" averaged motor vehicle octane rating system as posted on gas station pumps.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Sensitivity is roughly 8–10 points, meaning that a 91 AKI fuel might have a MON of as low as 86.
[src:gasoline/100ll] The extensive testing process required to obtain an STC for the engine/airframe combination helps ensure that, for those eligible aircraft, 91 AKI fuel provides sufficient detonation margin under normal conditions.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Automotive gasoline is not a fully viable replacement for avgas in many aircraft, because many high-performance and/or turbocharged airplane engines have been designed to use 100 octane fuel and modifications are necessary in order to use lower-octane fuel.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Many general aviation aircraft engines were designed to run on 80/87 octane, roughly the standard (as unleaded fuel only, with the "{R+M}/2" 87 octane rating) for North American automobiles today.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Direct conversions to run on automotive fuel are fairly common, by supplemental type certificate (STC).
[src:gasoline/100ll] However, the alloys used in aviation engine construction are chosen for their durability and synergistic relationship with the protective features of lead, and engine wear in the valves is a potential problem on automotive gasoline conversions.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Fortunately, significant history of engines converted to mogas has shown that very few engine problems are caused by automotive gasoline.
[src:gasoline/100ll] A larger problem stems from the higher and wider range of allowable vapor pressures found in automotive gasoline; this can pose some risk to aviation users if fuel system design considerations are not taken into account.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Automotive gasoline can vaporize in fuel lines, causing a vapor lock (a bubble in the line) or fuel pump cavitation, thereby starving the engine of fuel.
[src:gasoline/100ll] This does not constitute an insurmountable obstacle, but merely requires examination of the fuel system, ensuring adequate shielding from high temperatures and maintaining sufficient pressure in the fuel lines.
[src:gasoline/100ll] This is the main reason why both the specific engine model as well as the aircraft in which it is installed must be supplementally certified for the conversion.
[src:gasoline/100ll] A good example of this is the Piper Cherokee with high-compression 160 or 180 hp (120 or 130 kW) engines.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Only later versions of the airframe with different engine cowling and exhaust arrangements are applicable for the automotive fuel STC, and even then require fuel-system modifications.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Vapor lock typically occurs in fuel systems where a mechanically-driven fuel pump mounted on the engine draws fuel from a tank mounted lower than the pump.
[src:gasoline/100ll] The reduced pressure in the line can cause the more volatile components in automotive gasoline to flash into vapor, forming bubbles in the fuel line and interrupting fuel flow.
[src:gasoline/100ll] If an electric boost pump is mounted in the fuel tank to push fuel toward the engine, as is common practice in fuel-injected automobiles, the fuel pressure in the lines is maintained above ambient pressure, preventing bubble formation.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Likewise, if the fuel tank is mounted above the engine and fuel flows primarily due to gravity, as in a high-wing airplane, vapor lock cannot occur, using either aviation or automotive fuels.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Fuel-injected engines in automobiles also usually have a "fuel return" line to send unused fuel back to the tank, which has the benefit of equalizing the fuel's temperature throughout the system, further reducing the chance of vapor lock developing.
[src:gasoline/100ll] In addition to vapor locking potential, automotive gasoline does not have the same quality tracking as aviation gasoline.
[src:gasoline/100ll] To help solve this problem, the specification for an aviation fuel known as 82UL was developed as essentially automotive gasoline with additional quality tracking and restrictions on permissible additives.
[src:gasoline/100ll] This fuel is not currently in production and no refiners have committed to producing it.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Rotax allows up to 10% ethanol (similar to E10 fuel for cars) in the fuel for Rotax 912 engines.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Light sport aircraft that are specified by the manufacturer to tolerate alcohol in the fuel system can use up to 10% ethanol.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Fuel dyes aid ground crew and pilots in identifying and distinguishing the fuel grades and most are specified by ASTM D910 or other standards.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Dyes for the fuel are required in some countries.
[src:gasoline/100ll] The 100LL phase-out has been called "one of modern GA's most pressing problems", because 70% of 100LL aviation fuel is used by the 30% of the aircraft in the general aviation fleet that cannot use any of the existing alternatives.
[src:gasoline/100ll] The airframe must also be certified to use the fuel.
[src:gasoline/100ll] In February 2008, Teledyne Continental Motors (TCM) announced that the company is very concerned about future availability of 100LL, and as a result, they would develop a line of diesel engines.
[src:gasoline/100ll] In a February 2008 interview, TCM president Rhett Ross indicated belief that the aviation industry will be "forced out" of using 100LL in the near future, leaving automotive fuel and jet fuel as the only alternatives.
[src:gasoline/100ll] In May 2010, TCM announced that they had licensed development of the SMA SR305 diesel engine.
[src:gasoline/100ll] In November 2008, National Air Transportation Association's president Jim Coyne indicated that the environmental impact of aviation is expected to be a big issue over the next few years and will result in the phasing out of 100LL because of its lead content.
[src:gasoline/100ll] By May 2012, the US Federal Aviation Administration (FAA Unleaded Avgas Transition rulemaking committee) had put together a plan in conjunction with industry to replace leaded avgas with an unleaded alternative within 11 years.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Given the progress already made on 100SF and G100UL, the replacement time might be shorter than that 2023 estimate.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Each candidate fuel must meet a checklist of 12 fuel specification parameters and 4 distribution and storage parameters.
[src:gasoline/100ll] The FAA has requested a maximum of US$60M to fund the administration of the changeover.
[src:gasoline/100ll] In July 2014, nine companies and consortiums submitted proposals to the *Piston Aviation Fuels Initiative* (PAFI) to assess fuels without tetraethyl lead.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Phase one testing is performed at the William J.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Hughes Technical Center for a FAA approved industry replacement by 2018.
[src:gasoline/100ll] In July 2021, the first commercially-produced unleaded avgas, GAMI's G100UL, was approved by the Federal Aviation Administration through a Supplemental Type Certificate.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Lycoming Engines provides a list of engines and fuels that are compatible with unleaded fuel.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Prior to 2022, Teledyne Continental Motors (TCM) indicated that leaded avgas is required in their engines, and not unleaded auto fuels: "Current aircraft engines feature valve gear components which are designed for compatibility with the leaded ASTM D910 fuels.
[src:gasoline/100ll] In such fuels, the lead acts as a lubricant, coating the contact areas between the valve, guide, and seat.
[src:gasoline/100ll] They have announced a formal application to the FAA to approve the use of UL91 and UL94 in selected engines, stating that "Continental considers 91UL and 94UL fuel as a transitional step in a long-term strategy to reach a more sustainable aviation".
[src:gasoline/100ll] Hjelmco Oil first introduced unleaded Avgas grades in Europe in 2003, after its success with 80UL.
[src:gasoline/100ll] This grade of Avgas is manufactured to meet ASTM D7547.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Many common Lycoming engines are certified to run on this particular grade of Avgas, and Cessna has approved the use of this fuel in a large number of their piston fleet.
[src:gasoline/100ll] This fuel is also usable in any aircraft in Europe or the United Kingdom where the engine is certified to use it, whether or not the airframe is certified to do so, too.
[src:gasoline/100ll] The firm Airworthy AutoGas tested an ethanol-free 93 anti-knock index (AKI) premium auto gas on a Lycoming O-360-A4M in 2013.
[src:gasoline/100ll] The fuel is certified under Lycoming Service Instruction 1070 and ASTM D4814.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Unleaded 94 Motor octane fuel (*UL94*) is essentially 100LL without the lead.
[src:gasoline/100ll] In March 2009, Teledyne Continental Motors (TCM) announced they had tested a 94UL fuel that might be the best replacement for 100LL.
[src:gasoline/100ll] This 94UL meets the avgas specification including vapor pressure but has not been completely tested for detonation qualities in all Continental engines or under all conditions.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Flight testing has been conducted in an IO-550-B powering a Beechcraft Bonanza and ground testing in Continental O-200, 240, O-470, and O-520 engines.
[src:gasoline/100ll] In May 2010, TCM indicated that despite industry skepticism, they are proceeding with 94UL and that certification was expected in mid-2013.
[src:gasoline/100ll] In June 2010, Lycoming Engines indicated their opposition to 94UL.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Company general manager Michael Kraft stated that aircraft owners do not realize how much performance would be lost with 94UL and characterized the decision to pursue 94UL as a mistake that could cost the aviation industry billions in lost business.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Lycoming believes the industry should be pursuing 100UL instead.
[src:gasoline/100ll] The Lycoming position is supported by aircraft type clubs representing owners of aircraft that would be unable to run on lower octane fuel.
[src:gasoline/100ll] In June 2010, clubs such as the American Bonanza Society, the Malibu Mirage Owners and Pilots Association, and the Cirrus Owners and Pilots Association collectively formed the *Clean 100 Octane Coalition* to represent them on this issue and push for unleaded 100 octane avgas.
[src:gasoline/100ll] In November 2015, UL94 was added as a secondary grade of unleaded aviation gasoline to ASTM D7547, which is the specification that governs UL91 unleaded avgas.
[src:gasoline/100ll] UL94 meets all of the same specification property limits as 100LL with the exception of a lower motor octane number (94.0 minimum for UL94 vs.
[src:gasoline/100ll] 99.6 minimum for 100LL) and a decreased maximum lead content.
[src:gasoline/100ll] UL94 is an unleaded fuel, but as with all ASTM International unleaded gasoline specifications, a *de minimis* amount of unintentionally added lead is permitted.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Since May 2016, UL94, now a product of Swift Fuels, is available for sale at dozens of airports in the United States.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Swift Fuels has an agreement for distribution in Europe.
[src:gasoline/100ll] UL94 is not intended to be a full replacement for 100LL, but rather is designed to be a drop-in replacement for aircraft with lower-octane-rated engines, such as those that are approved for operation on Grade 80 avgas (or lower), UL91, or mogas.
[src:gasoline/100ll] It is estimated that up to 65% of the fleet of current general aviation piston-engine-powered aircraft can operate on UL94 with no modifications to either the engine or airframe.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Some aircraft, however, do require a FAA-approved Supplemental Type Certificate (STC) to be purchased to allow for operation on UL94.
[src:gasoline/100ll] UL94 has a minimum Motor octane number (MON, which is the octane rating employed for grading aviation gasoline) of 94.0.
[src:gasoline/100ll] AKI is the octane rating used to grade all U.S. automotive gasoline (typical values at the pump can include 87, 89, 91, and 93), and also the 93UL fuel from Airworthy AutoGas.
[src:gasoline/100ll] The minimum AKI of UL94, as sold by Swift Fuels, is 98.0.
[src:gasoline/100ll] The publication of the SAIB, especially the August 2016 revision, eliminated the need for many of the UL94 STCs being sold by Swift Fuels, as the majority of the aircraft on the STC's Approved Model List are type-certified to use 80-octane or lower avgas.
[src:gasoline/100ll] On April 6, 2017, Lycoming Engines published Service Instruction 1070V, which adds UL94 as an approved grade of fuel for dozens of engine models, 60% of which are carbureted engines.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Engines with displacements of 235, 320, 360, and 540 cubic inches make up almost 90% of the models approved for UL94.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Swift Fuels, LLC, has attained approval to produce fuel for testing at its pilot plant in Indiana.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Composed of approximately 85% mesitylene and 15% isopentane, the fuel is reportedly scheduled for extensive testing by the FAA to receive certification under the new ASTM D7719 guideline for unleaded 100LL replacement fuels.
[src:gasoline/100ll] The company eventually intends to produce the fuel from renewable biomass feedstocks, and aims to produce something competitive in price with 100LL and currently available alternative fuels.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Swift Fuels has suggested that the fuel, formerly referred to as 100SF, will be available for "high performance piston-powered aircraft" before 2020.
[src:gasoline/100ll] John and Mary-Louise Rusek founded Swift Enterprises in 2001 to develop renewable fuels and hydrogen fuel cells.
[src:gasoline/100ll] They began testing "Swift 142" in 2006 and patented several alternatives for non-alcohol based fuels which can be derived from biomass fermentation.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Over the next several years, the company sought to build a pilot plant to produce enough fuel for larger-scale testing and submitted fuel to the FAA for testing.
[src:gasoline/100ll] In 2008, an article by technology writer and aviation enthusiast Robert X.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Cringely attracted popular attention to the fuel, as also did a cross-country Swift-Fueled flight by the AOPA's Dave Hirschman.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Swift Enterprises' claims that the fuel could eventually be manufactured much more cheaply than 100LL have been debated in the aviation press.
[src:gasoline/100ll] The FAA found Swift Fuel to have a motor octane number of 104.4, 96.3% of the energy per unit of mass, and 113% of the energy per unit of volume as 100LL, and to meet most of the ASTM D910 standard for leaded aviation fuel.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Following tests in two Lycoming engines, the FAA concluded it performs better than 100LL in detonation testing and will provide a fuel saving of 8% per unit of volume, though it weighs 1 pound per US gallon (120 g/L) more than 100LL.
[src:gasoline/100ll] GC–FID testing showed the fuel to be made primarily of two components — one about 85% by weight and the other about 14% by weight.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Soon afterward, AVweb reported that Continental had begun the process of certifying several of its engines to use the new fuel.
[src:gasoline/100ll] In 2012, Swift Fuels LLC was formed to bring in oil and gas industry experience, scale up production and bring the fuel to market.
[src:gasoline/100ll] By November 2013, the company had built its pilot plant and received approval to produce fuel in it.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Its most recent patent, approved in 2013, describes methods by which the fuel can be produced from fermentable biomass.
[src:gasoline/100ll] The FAA scheduled UL102 for 2 years of phase 2 testing in its PAFI initiative beginning in the summer of 2016.
[src:gasoline/100ll] In February 2010, General Aviation Modifications Inc.
[src:gasoline/100ll] (GAMI) announced that it was in the process of developing a 100LL replacement to be called G100UL ("unleaded").
[src:gasoline/100ll] This fuel is made by blending existing refinery products and yields detonation margins comparable to 100LL.
[src:gasoline/100ll] The new fuel is slightly more dense than 100LL, but has a 3.5% higher thermodynamic output.
[src:gasoline/100ll] G100UL is compatible with 100LL and can be mixed with it in aircraft tanks for use.
[src:gasoline/100ll] In demonstrations held in July 2010, G100UL performed better than 100LL that just meets the minimum specification and performed as well as average production 100LL.
[src:gasoline/100ll] G100UL was approved by the Federal Aviation Administration by the issuance of a Supplemental Type Certificate at AirVenture in July 2021.
[src:gasoline/100ll] The STC was initially only applicable to Lycoming-powered models of the Cessna 172.
[src:gasoline/100ll] The company indicated that the retail cost was expected to be 0.60–0.85 US dollars per US gallon higher than 100LL.
[src:gasoline/100ll] This was later revised to 1.00 US dollar per US gallon.
[src:gasoline/100ll] In 2022, Paul Bertorelli of AVweb reported that the FAA was dragging its feet on broadly certifying G100UL, delaying approval of the fuel for more engines and spending over $80 million on EAGLE to re-start a search for an unleaded fuel when G100UL had been under evaluation for over 10 years.
[src:gasoline/100ll] In September 2022, in a surprise announcement, the FAA approved an STC for the use of the fuel for all piston-engined aircraft and engine combinations.
[src:gasoline/100ll] In February 2023, GAMI began selling supplemental type certificates to allow aircraft owners to use the fuel when it becomes available.
[src:gasoline/100ll] In April 2024, GAMI announced that 1 million gallons of G100UL had been produced.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Fuel availability in the US was forecast for airports in California, Washington and Oregon by the middle of 2024 and the rest of the country by 2026.
[src:gasoline/100ll] In December 2024, shortly after G100UL was made available at selected airports in California, several concerns regarding material compatibility arose, as users reported fuel leaks, paint staining, and paint stripping.
[src:gasoline/100ll] In December 2013, Shell Oil announced that they had developed an unleaded 100 octane fuel and will submit it for FAA testing with certification expected within two to three years.
[src:gasoline/100ll] The fuel is alkylate-based with an additive package of aromatics.
[src:gasoline/100ll] No information has yet been published with regard to its performance, producibility or price.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Industry analysts have indicated that it will likely cost as much as or more than existing 100LL.
[src:gasoline/100ll] In 2018, LyondellBasell and VP Racing Fuels, an established motorsport fuel manufacturer, announced its intention to participate in developing an unleaded fuel for piston-powered aircraft.
[src:gasoline/100ll] As of December 2024, it has reached Phase 4 of testing, according to the FAA.
[src:gasoline/100ll] TEL found in leaded avgas and its combustion products are potent neurotoxins that have been shown in scientific research to interfere with brain development in children.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Children in residences or childcare facilities in close proximity to airports with moderate to high piston engine aircraft traffic are at especially high risk of high blood lead levels.
[src:gasoline/100ll] On November 16, 2007, the environmental group Friends of the Earth formally petitioned the EPA, asking them to regulate leaded avgas.
[src:gasoline/100ll] The EPA responded with a notice of petition for rulemaking.
[src:gasoline/100ll] The public comment period on this petition closed on March 17, 2008.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Under a federal court order to set a new standard by October 15, 2008, the EPA cut the acceptable limits for atmospheric lead from the previous standard of 1.5 μg/m3 to 0.15 μg/m3.
[src:gasoline/100ll] This was the first change to the standard since 1978 and represents an order of magnitude reduction over previous levels.
[src:gasoline/100ll] The EPA's own studies have shown that to prevent a measurable decrease in IQ for children deemed most vulnerable, the standard needs to be set much lower, to 0.02 μg/m3.
[src:gasoline/100ll] The EPA identified avgas as one of the most "significant sources of lead".
[src:gasoline/100ll] In December 2008, AOPA filed formal comments to the new EPA regulations.
[src:gasoline/100ll] AOPA has asked the EPA to account for the cost and the safety issues involved with removing lead from avgas.
[src:gasoline/100ll] They cited that the aviation sector employs more than 1.3 million people in the US and has an economic direct and indirect effect that "exceeds $150 billion annually".
[src:gasoline/100ll] AOPA interprets the new regulations as not affecting general aviation as they are currently written.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Publication in the USA Federal Register of an Advance Notice of Proposed Rulemaking by the USA EPA occurred in April 2010.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Despite assertions in the media that leaded avgas will be eliminated in the US by 2017 at the latest date, the EPA confirmed in July 2010 that there is no phase-out date and that setting one would be an FAA responsibility as the EPA has no authority over avgas.
[src:gasoline/100ll] The FAA administrator stated that regulating lead in avgas is an EPA responsibility, resulting in widespread criticism of both organizations for causing confusion and delaying solutions.
[src:gasoline/100ll] "There is no reason to believe 100 low-lead will become unavailable in the foreseeable future," Fuller stated.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Final results from EPA's lead modeling study at the Santa Monica Airport shows off-airport levels below current 150 ng/m3 and possible future 20 ng/m3 levels.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Fifteen of 17 airports monitored during a year-long study in the US by the EPA have lead emissions well below the current National Ambient Air Quality Standard (NAAQS) for lead.
[src:gasoline/100ll] Avgas is occasionally used in amateur auto racing cars as its octane rating is higher than automotive gasoline thus allowing the engines to run at higher compression ratios.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In an effort that was led by Faisal of Saudi Arabia, the initial countries that OAPEC targeted were Canada, Japan, the Netherlands, the United Kingdom, and the United States.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] This list was later expanded to include Portugal, Rhodesia, and South Africa.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In March 1974, OAPEC lifted the embargo, but the price of oil had risen by nearly 300%: from US$3 per barrel ($19/m3) to nearly US$12 per barrel ($75/m3) globally.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Prices in the United States were significantly higher than the global average.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After it was implemented, the embargo caused an oil crisis, or "shock", with many short- and long-term effects on the global economy as well as on global politics.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The 1973 embargo later came to be referred to as the **first oil shock**.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] A second oil shock occurred in 1979 in the aftermath of the Iranian Revolution.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Following the Israeli Declaration of Independence in 1948, there has been conflict between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East, including several wars.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Suez Crisis, also known as the Second Arab–Israeli war, was sparked by Israel's southern port of Eilat being blocked by Egypt, which also nationalized the Suez Canal belonging to French and British investors.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] As a result of the war, the Suez Canal was closed for several months between 1956 and 1957.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Six-Day War of 1967 included an Israeli invasion of the Egyptian Sinai Peninsula, which resulted in Egypt closing the Suez Canal for eight years.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Following the Yom Kippur War, the canal was cleared in 1974 and opened again in 1975.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OAPEC countries cut production of oil and placed an embargo on oil exports to the United States after Richard Nixon requested $2.2 billion to support Israel's war effort.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nevertheless, the embargo lasted only until January 1974, though the price of oil remained high afterwards.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] By 1969, American domestic production of oil was peaking and could not keep pace with increasing demand from vehicles.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The US was importing 350 million barrels (56 million cubic metres) per year by the late 1950s, mostly from Venezuela and Canada.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Because of transportation costs and tariffs, it never purchased much oil from the Middle East.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1973, US production had declined to 16% of global output.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Eisenhower imposed quotas on foreign oil that would stay in place between 1959 and 1973.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Critics called it the "drain America first" policy.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Some scholars believe the policy contributed to the decline of domestic US oil production in the early 1970s.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The cheapness of oil compared with coal led to the decline of the coal industry.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1951, 51% of the United States' energy came from coal, and by 1973, only 19% of American industry was coal-based.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The decline in domestic oil production, combined with the country's increasing reliance on oil as a source of power, made the US economy vulnerable to a foreign oil embargo.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] When Richard Nixon became US president in 1969, he assigned George Shultz to head a committee to review the Eisenhower-era quota program.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Shultz's committee recommended that the quotas be abolished and replaced with tariffs, but Nixon decided to keep the quotas due to vigorous political opposition.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon imposed a price ceiling on oil in August 1971 as demand for oil was increasing and production was declining, which increased dependence on oil imports as consumption was bolstered by low prices.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1973, Nixon announced the end of the quota system.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Between 1970 and 1973 US imports of crude oil had nearly doubled, reaching 6.2 million barrels per day in 1973.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Until 1973, an abundance of oil supply had kept the market price of oil lower than the posted price.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1970, American oil production peaked and the United States began to import more oil.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Oil imports rose by 52% between 1969 and 1972.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] By 1972, 83% of the American oil imports came from the Middle East.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Throughout the 1960s, the price for a barrel of oil remained at $1.80, meaning that with the effects of inflation considered the price of oil in real terms got progressively lower throughout the decade, with Americans paying less for oil in 1969 than they had in 1959.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Even after a price for a barrel of oil rose to $2.00 in 1971, adjusted for inflation, people in the Western nations were paying less for oil in 1971 than they had in 1958.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The extremely low price of oil served as the basis for the "long summer" of prosperity and mass affluence that began in 1945.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC), was founded by five oil producing countries at a Baghdad conference on 14 September 1960.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The five founding members of OPEC were Venezuela, Iraq, Saudi Arabia, Iran and Kuwait.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OPEC was organized after the oil companies slashed the posted price of oil, but the posted price of oil remained consistently higher than the market price of oil between 1961 and 1972.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1963, the Seven Sisters controlled 86% of the oil produced by OPEC countries, but by 1970 the rise of "independent oil companies" had decreased their share to 77%.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The entry of three new oil producers—Algeria, Libya and Nigeria—meant that by 1970, 81 oil companies were doing business in the Middle East.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In the early 1960s Libya, Indonesia and Qatar joined OPEC.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OPEC was generally regarded as ineffective until political turbulence in Libya and Iraq strengthened their position in 1970.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Additionally, increasing Soviet influence provided oil producing countries with alternative means of transporting oil to markets.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Under the Tehran Price Agreement of 1971, signed on 14 February, the posted price of oil was increased and, due to a decline in the value of the US dollar relative to gold, certain anti-inflationary measures were enacted.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] A severe drain on US gold reserves lead to higher inflation and lack of confidence in the strength of the dollar, President Nixon issued Executive Order 11615 on August 15, 1971, which closed the gold window.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] This action made the dollar inconvertible to gold directly, except on the open market, and was soon dubbed the *Nixon Shock*, leading eventually to the collapse of the Bretton Woods system in 1976.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Because oil was priced in dollars, oil producers' real income decreased when the dollar started to float free of the old link to gold.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In September 1971, OPEC issued a joint communiqué stating that from then on, they would price oil in terms of a fixed amount of gold.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After 1971, OPEC was slow to readjust prices to reflect this depreciation.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] From 1947 to 1967, the dollar price of oil had risen by less than two percent per year.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Until the oil shock, the price had also remained fairly stable versus other currencies and commodities.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OPEC ministers had not developed institutional mechanisms to update prices in sync with changing market conditions, so their real incomes lagged.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The substantial price increases of 1973–1974 largely returned their prices and corresponding incomes to former levels in terms of commodities such as gold.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Arab oil producing countries had attempted to use oil as leverage to influence political events on two prior occasions—the first was the Suez Crisis in 1956 when the United Kingdom, France and Israel invaded Egypt.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] During the conflict the Syrians sabotaged both the Trans-Arabian Pipeline and the Iraq–Baniyas pipeline, which disrupted the supply of oil to Western Europe.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The second instance was when war broke out between Egypt and Israel in 1967, but despite continued Egyptian and Syrian enmity against Israel, the embargo lasted only a few months.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Most scholars agree that the 1967 embargo was ineffective.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Although some members of the Organization of Arab Petroleum Exporting Countries (OAPEC) supported the use of oil as a weapon to influence the political outcome of the Arab–Israeli conflict, Saudi Arabia had traditionally been the strongest supporter of separating oil from politics.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Saudis were wary of the tactic due to the availability of oil from non-Arab oil producing countries, and in the decades leading up to the crisis, the region's conservative monarchies had grown dependent on Western support to ensure their continued survival as Nasserism gained traction.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On the other hand, Algeria, Iraq and Libya had strongly supported the use of oil as a weapon in the conflict.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Arab newspapers like the Egyptian *Al-Ahram*, Lebanese *An-Nahar* and Iraqi *Al-Thawra* had historically been supportive of the use of oil as a weapon.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1970, President Nasser of Egypt died and was succeeded by Anwar Sadat, a man who believed in the diplomacy of surprise, in engaging in sudden moves to upset the diplomatic equilibrium.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Sadat liked to say that his favourite game was backgammon, a game where skill and persistence was rewarded, but was best won by sudden gambles, making an analogy between how he played backgammon and conducted his diplomacy.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Under Nasser, Egypt and Saudi Arabia had engaged what was known as the Arab Cold War, but Sadat got along very well with King Faisal of Saudi Arabia, forming an alliance between the most populous Arab state and the wealthiest Arab state.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Unlike the secularist Nasser, Sadat was a pious Muslim and he had a strong personal rapport with King Faisal, who was an equally pious Muslim.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The man largely in charge of American foreign policy, the National Security Adviser, Henry Kissinger, later admitted that he was so engrossed with the Paris peace talks to end the Vietnam war that he and others in Washington missed the significance of the Egyptian-Saudi alliance.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At the same time that Sadat moved closer to Saudi Arabia, he also wanted a rapprochement with the United States and to move Egypt away from its alliance with the Soviet Union.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1971, the US had information that the Arab states were willing to implement another embargo.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In July 1972, Sadat expelled all 16,000 of the Soviet military personnel in Egypt in a signal that he wanted better relations with the United States.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger was taken completely by surprise by Sadat's move, saying: "Why has he done me this favor?
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] For Sadat, cost was no object as the money to buy Soviet arms came from Saudi Arabia.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At the same time, Faisal promised Sadat that if it should come to war, Saudi Arabia would embargo oil to the West.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In April 1973, the Saudi Oil Minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani visited Washington to meet Kissinger and told him that King Faisal was becoming more and more unhappy with the United States, saying he wanted America to pressure Israel to return all the lands captured in the Six Day War of 1967.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In a later interview, Yamani accused Kissinger of not taking his warning seriously, saying all he did was to ask him not to speak anymore of this threat.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Angry at Kissinger, Yamani, in an interview with the *Washington Post* on April 19, 1973, warned that King Faisal was considering an oil embargo.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At the time, the general feeling in Washington was the Saudis were bluffing and nothing would come of their threat to impose an oil embargo.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The fact that Faisal's ineffectual half brother King Saud had imposed a crippling oil embargo on Britain and France during the Suez War of 1956 was not considered an important precedent.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The CEOs of four of the United States' oil companies, after speaking with Faisal, arrived in Washington in May 1973 with the warning that Faisal was considerably tougher, more intelligent and more ruthless than his half-brother Saud whom he had deposed in 1964, and that his threats were serious.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger declined to meet the four CEOs.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In an assessment done by Kissinger and his staff about the Middle East in the summer of 1973, the repeated statements by Sadat about waging *jihad* against Israel were dismissed as empty talk, while the warnings from King Faisal were likewise regarded as inconsequential.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In September 1973, Nixon fired Rogers as Secretary of State and replaced him with Kissinger.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger later stated he had not been given enough time to know the Middle East, as he settled into the State Department's office at Foggy Bottom as Egypt and Syria attacked Israel on 6 October 1973.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 6 October 1973, the Yom Kippur began when Egypt attacked the Bar Lev Line in the Sinai Peninsula and Syria launched an offensive in the Golan Heights, both of which had been occupied by Israel during the 1967 Six-Day War.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal of Saudi Arabia was supportive, and on 8 October 1973, he told two Egyptian envoys: "You have made us all proud.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In the past we could not lift our heads up.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] He promised to give to Egypt a quality of aid worth $200 million US dollars to assist with the war effort, and stated he was willing to use the "oil weapon" if necessary to support Egypt.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The war began during the height of the Watergate scandal; as such Nixon largely let Kissinger manage foreign policy as he, Nixon, was distracted by the scandal.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger promised Israeli Prime Minister Golda Meir that the United States would replace its losses in equipment after the war.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon had ordered an arms lift to Israel on 12 October 1973, but Kissinger used the excuse of bureaucratic delays to limit the amount of weapons and ammunition sent to Israel.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Arab concept of the "peace of the brave", i.e. a victorious leader being magnanimous to his defeated opponents, meant there was a possibility that Sadat at least would make peace with Israel provided that the war ended in such a way that Egypt was not perceived to be defeated.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Likewise, Kissinger regarded Meir as being rather arrogant and believed that an armistice that ended the war in a manner that was not an unambiguous Israeli victory would make her more humble.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] As both Syria and Egypt lost much equipment during the fighting, the Soviet Union began to fly new equipment in, starting on 12 October.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Soviet flights to Syria and Egypt were recorded by the British radar stations in Cyprus.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Though the Soviets were flying in an average of 60 flights per day, exaggerated accounts appeared in Western newspapers speaking of "one hundred flights per day".
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At this point, both Nixon and Kissinger began to see the October War more in terms of the Cold War rather than Middle Eastern politics, both seeing the Soviet arms lifts to Egypt and Syria as a Soviet power play that required an American answer.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On October 12, 1973, US president Richard Nixon authorized Operation Nickel Grass, a strategic airlift to deliver weapons and supplies to Israel in order to replace its materiel losses.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The first American weapons to Israel arrived on 15 October 1973, and despite Nixon's orders the number of American planes flying into Tel Aviv were initially limited.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After the first week of the war, the Israelis had halted the Syrian offensive in the Golan Heights and were pushing back the Syrians back towards Damascus.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Along the Suez canal, however, there was heavy fighting, with the Egyptians holding their own.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At an OPEC summit at the Sheraton Hotel in Kuwait City on 16 October 1973, it was announced the price of oil would go from $3.01 US dollars per barrel to $5.12 per barrel.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The news about the war on 16 October was grim from the Arab viewpoint, with the Syrians steadily being pushed back, while Israelis had opened a counter-offensive against the Egyptians and crossed the Great Bitter Lake.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Responses from stated representatives at the meeting were varied.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Saudi Oil Minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani stated, in a 1981 interview, that "[t]he king still wanted to give America a chance to stay out of the fighting.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] So we agreed to cut back production by just 5 percent per month.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] A full embargo, we agreed, was something we would implement only if we felt that things were absolutely hopeless".
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Iranian delegation left the summit after agreeing to the price increase, as the Shah of Iran only supported higher oil prices.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Oil Minister of Iraq, Sa'dun Hammadi demanded the "total nationalization" of all assets of American oil companies in the Middle East, the withdrawal of all Arab funds from the United States and for all Arab states to break diplomatic relations with the United States.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Libyan Oil Minister, Izz al-Din al-Mabruk, called for the nationalization of all the assets of all Western oil companies in the Middle East.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Saudi delegation led by Yemani, supported by the Algerian delegation, fought hard against the Iraqi and Libyan demands for an embargo, as Yemani maintained that forcing through an increase in the price of oil was the best way to influence the United States.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Hammadi and the rest of the Iraqi delegation left upset as Yemani had won over the majority of the delegations to the Saudi viewpoint.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The statement issued after midnight at the Sheraton Hotel was handwritten and, reflecting the tense talk, had several paragraphs crossed out while other paragraphs were written in by different hands.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 17 October, Arab oil producers cut production by 5% and threatened an oil embargo against Israel's wartime allies: the United States, the Netherlands, Rhodesia, South Africa, and Portugal.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 17–19 October 1973, the Saudi Foreign Minister, Omar Al Saqqaf, visited Washington together with the foreign ministers of Algeria, Kuwait and Morocco to warn that there was a real possibility of an oil embargo being imposed.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon promised him that the United States would mediate a settlement to the war that would be "peaceful, just and honorable" to both sides.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] He had ended the Vietnam war on what he felt was an honorable basis and now intended to end the October war in the same manner.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Saqqaf complained to King Faisal that Nixon seemed more interested in a dispute about "a burglary" (i.e. the Watergate scandal) than about the war.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] During a press conference, an American reporter mocked the threat of an embargo, contemptuously saying the Saudis "could drink their oil", leading Saqqaf to reply in anger "All right, we will!".
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Israel took heavy losses in men and materiel during the fighting against Egypt and Syria, and on 18 October 1973, Meir requested $850 million worth of American arms and equipment to replace its materiel losses.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon decided, characteristically, to act on an epic scale; Instead of the $850 million worth of arms requested, he sent a request to Congress for some $2.2 billion worth of arms to Israel, which was promptly approved.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon, whose administration was being badly battered by the Watergate scandal, felt that a bold foreign policy move might resuscitate his administration.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In an interview with the British historian Robert Lacey in 1981, Kissinger later admitted about the arms lift to Israel: "I made a mistake.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In retrospect it was not the best considered decision we made".
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The arms lift enraged King Faisal of Saudi Arabia.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal was angry that Israel had only asked for $850 million worth of American weapons, and instead received an unsolicited $2.2 billion worth of weapons, which he perceived as a sign of the pro-Israeli slant of American foreign policy.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal also felt insulted that Nixon had just promised Saqqaf an "honorable" peace the day before he submitted the request to Congress for some $2.2 billion worth of arms for Israel, which he saw as an act of duplicity on Nixon's part.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal had been opposed to a total embargo and only agreed to the 5% cut on 17 October under pressure from other Arab states.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal felt his efforts on behalf the United States were not being appreciated in Washington, which increased his fury at Nixon.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On the afternoon of 19 October 1973, Faisal was in his office when he learned about the United States sending $2.2 billion worth of weapons to Israel, and discussed the issue with two of his closest advisers, Abdullah ibn Abdul Rahman and Rashad Pharaon.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The king called Yamani at about 8 pm, and told him he was needed at the Riyassa Palace immediately.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Yamani told the king: "The TV news goes out at nine.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] If you make a decision now, we can get it announced at once".
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The king replied "Write this down" and announced he was placing a total embargo on the United States.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Most of the other oil-producing Arab states joined the embargo.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Algeria, Iraq, and Libya promoted the embargo, but did not actively enforce it.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo was accompanied by gradual monthly production cuts—by December, production had been cut to 25% of September levels.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] This contributed to a global recession and increased tension between the United States and several of its European allies, who faulted the US for provoking an embargo by providing what many viewed as unconditional assistance to Israel.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OAPEC demanded a complete Israeli withdrawal from all territories beyond the 1949 Armistice border.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo lasted from October 1973 to March 1974.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Because every Arab state except for Iraq and Libya joined the oil embargo, oil exports from the Middle East to the West were down by 60–70% by November 1973.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Japan and the nations of western Europe imported some 75% of their oil from the Near East.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo led to immediate and sharp price raises, as Lacey noted that "competing desperately for dwindling supplies, consumers showed themselves willing to pay unparalleled money for their oil".
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Saudi Arabia had 25% of the world's oil reserves.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo imposed on the United States led to shortages of oil in the United States, which set an inflationary spiral, as the new high prices for oil in the American market led to sharp increases of the price of oil in nations not subjected to the embargo.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] When the Iranian state oil company held an auction on 16 December 1973, bids for some $17 US dollars per barrel of oil were made.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In late December 1973, OPEC held a conference in Vienna when it was announced the price for a barrel of oil was to increase from $5 US dollars per barrel to $11.65 US dollars per barrel.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal was opposed to the price increase, which was largely the work of the Iranian delegation.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 22 February 1974, King Faisal chaired the second summit of Islamic states in Lahore, which, unlike the first summit that Faisal had chaired in 1969, was not boycotted by Iraq and Syria.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal was acclaimed as a conquering hero who humiliated and humbled the West by wrecking its economy.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The prime minister of Pakistan, Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, opened the conference by stating: "The armies of Pakistan are the armies of Islam.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On November 7, 1973, Kissinger flew to Riyadh to meet King Faisal and ask him to end the oil embargo in exchange for promising to be "evenhanded" with the Arab-Israeli dispute.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] As the plane carrying him prepared to land in Riyadh, Kissinger was clearly nervous at the prospect of negotiating with the stern Wahhabi Faisal who had a marked dislike of Jews.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] During a summit in Cairo the day before, Kissinger asked Sadat what Faisal was like and was told: "Well, Dr.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Henry, he will probably go on with you about Communism and the Jews".
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] King Faisal's two great hatreds were communism and Zionism, as he believed that the Soviet Union and Israel were plotting together against Islam.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Initially, Secretary of Defense James Schlesinger suggested to Kissinger that the USA invade Saudi Arabia and another Arab countries and seize their oil fields.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger stated in a private state department meeting that it's “ridiculous that the civilized world is held up by 8 million savages...
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Can’t we overthrow one of the sheikhs just to show that we can do it?” They formed a plan to invade Abu Dhabi, Kuwait, and Saudi Arabia.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger publicly threatened "countermeasures" in a November 21, 1973 press conference if the embargo was not lifted, and the Saudis responded with threatening further oil cuts and to burn their oil fields if the US military invaded.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After the CIA confirmed these threats, Kissinger gave up military intervention and decided to deal with Israel's troop withdrawals, settling on diplomatic solutions to the oil embargo.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 18 March 1974, King Faisal ended the oil embargo.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Sadat had reported to Faisal that the United States was being more "evenhanded", and Kissinger had promised to sell Saudi Arabia weapons that it had previously denied under the grounds that they might be used against Israel.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Since Israeli forces did not withdraw to the 1949 Armistice Line, the majority of scholars believe that the embargo was a failure.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Roy Licklieder, in his 1988 book *Political Power and the Arab Oil Weapon*, concluded that the embargo was a failure because the countries that were targeted by the embargo did not change their policies on the Arab–Israeli conflict.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Licklieder believed that any long term changes were caused by the OPEC increase in the posted price of oil, and not the OAPEC embargo.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Daniel Yergin, on the other hand, has said that the embargo "remade the international economy".
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Over the long term, the oil embargo changed the nature of policy in the West towards increased exploration, alternative energy research, energy conservation and more restrictive monetary policy to better fight inflation.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p01] For further details see the "Energy crisis" series by Facts on File.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The effects of the embargo were immediate.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] OPEC forced oil companies to increase payments drastically.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The price of oil quadrupled by 1974 from US$3 to nearly US$12 per 42 gallon barrel ($75 per cubic meter), equivalent in 2018 dollars to a price rise from $17 to $61 per barrel.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Saudi Arabia had 25% of the world's oil, but only 4% of the oil used in the United States in 1973 came from the kingdom.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] However, Saudi Arabia plays an over-sized role within the Arab world.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1973, about 25% of the oil used in the United States came from Arab countries.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The shortage of oil within the United States caused by the Arab oil embargo forced prices to rise, which led price rises globally.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Oil producers that had not joined the embargo such as Iran, Venezuela, Libya and Iraq demanded higher prices in Japan and Europe, as an initiative to ship oil to those places instead of the United States, setting off a worldwide inflationary spiral.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Although the embargo did not severely disrupt US oil supplies—since Americans imported more oil from non-embargoed nations such as Iran—the resulting 400% increase in oil prices caused by the embargo damaged the American economy.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A number of nations such as Venezuela, Nigeria, Iran and Iraq increased their oil production during the embargo, and sold their oil at a higher price.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The leader who pushed the most for higher oil prices was the Shah of Iran, and the Italian historian Giuliano Garavini has argued that the leader most responsible for the West's economic problems during the "oil shock" was not King Faisal, but rather the Shah.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Some of the nations that were classified as "friendly" to the Arab viewpoint in regards to the Arab-Israeli dispute such as France and Belgium were the ones who suffered the most from the worldwide inflation caused by the embargo.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In March 1974, the crisis eased when the embargo was lifted after negotiations at the Washington Oil Summit, but the effects lingered throughout the 1970s.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The dollar price of energy increased again in 1975, amid the weakening competitive position of the dollar in world markets.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Arab oil embargo ended the long period of prosperity in the West that had begun in 1945, throwing the world's economy into the steepest economic contraction since the Great Depression.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The "long summer" of prosperity in the post-war years had made possible the "swinging sixties" and the related rise of a rebellious youth culture, as it was easy to be hedonist or in rebellion against traditional values in a time of unprecedented prosperity.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] 1945 to 1973 had been a period of unprecedented prosperity in the West, a "long summer" that many believed would never end.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Its abrupt end in 1973, as the oil embargo increased the price of oil by 400% within a matter of days and threw the world's economy into a sharp recession, with unemployment mounting and inflation raging, came as a profound shock.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The end of what the French called the *Trente Glorieuses* ("Glorious Thirty" [years]) led to widespread pessimism in the West, with the *Financial Times* running a famous headline in late 1973 saying, "The Future will be subject to Delay".
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In an August 1974 address to the General Assembly, Kurt Waldheim, the secretary-general of the United Nations, complained about "the note of helplessness and fatalism creeping into world affairs".
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The sudden and abrupt end of the "long summer" of prosperity in 1973-1974 played a major role in the pessimistic mood that characterized the culture of the West of the 1970s.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1975, a report to Congress from the Federal Energy Administration estimated that the embargo of 1973–1974 had caused about 500,000 Americans to lose their jobs, and caused a GNP loss between $10 billion–$20 billion.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] This price increase had a dramatic effect on oil exporting nations, for the countries of the Middle East who had long been dominated by the industrial powers were seen to have taken control of a vital commodity.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil-exporting nations began to accumulate vast wealth.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Some of the income was dispensed in the form of aid to other underdeveloped nations whose economies had been caught between higher oil prices and lower prices for their own export commodities, amid shrinking Western demand.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Much went for arms purchases that exacerbated political tensions, particularly in the Middle East.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The 400% increase in the world oil prices led to extravagant promises being made by the leaders of oil-producing nations.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Shah of Iran told his subjects in a speech in December 1973 that he was launching "Great Civilization" project that would make Iran into a First World nation by the 1990s.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] President Carlos Andrés Pérez of Venezuela likewise launched his *Le Gran Venezuela* project intended to make Venezuela into a First World nation.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] President Yakubu Gowon of Nigeria told his people that henceforward Nigeria's main problem would be "managing abundance".
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] After the oil shock, Nigeria presented itself as the first African nation that would reach First World status.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In Lagos, a series of stately modernist buildings were erected as appropriate for a nation that saw itself as the leader of all Black Africa.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Much of the oil wealth in Nigeria was stolen by corrupt politicians.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] At least some of Nigeria's new oil wealth went to rebuild the areas devastated by the civil war of 1967-1970 and to address the complaints that too much of Nigeria's oil wealth went to the federal government in Lagos instead of the people.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The new wealth generated by the "oil shock" allowed for Chairman Houari Boumédiène of Algeria to become a global leader, courted by elites in the First World and the Third World.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil embargo led a sudden interest in the Palestinian issue.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Between 1973 and 1981, Saudi Arabia donated a sum worth $1 billion US dollars to the Palestine Liberation Organization, which thus had a budget that exceeded that of many Third World nations.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On November 8, 1973, Kissinger became the first Secretary of State to meet with a Saudi leader since 1953, as he met King Faisal to ask him to end the embargo.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Within two week of the embargo being launched, all of the foreign ministers of the nations of the European Economic Community, now the European Union, met in a conference to issue a statement calling for Israel "to end the territorial occupation which has maintained since the conflict of 1967".
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On December 11, 1973, the Japanese Foreign Minister Masayoshi Ōhira flew in to Riyadh to meet King Faisal for "talks on improving bilateral relations".
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Shortly afterwards, the French foreign minister Michel Jobert arrived to sign an agreement that provided oil for France for the next twenty years.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On January 24, 1974, as the Shah of Iran, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, was coming off the ski slopes of St.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Moritz, he was met by the British Chancellor of Exchequer, Anthony Barber, and the Trade Secretary, Peter Walker.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In a role-reversal, Barber and Walker paid homage to the Shah, who promised them that his nation would sell the United Kingdom 5 million tons of oil in exchange for some £100 million of British goods, to aid his plans to industrialize Iran.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Saudi Arabia experienced an upsurge of prosperity and affluence after the oil embargo, whose consequences horrified King Faisal.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Faisal, who was devoted to a harsh puritanical strain of Sunni Islam known in the West as Wahhabism, was appalled by the way that his subjects became materialistic, devoted only to conspicuous consumption and greed as they lost interest in Islam.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Lacey wrote: "The spiritual dangers of easy affluence distressed him more.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] His simple gesture of piety and honor seemed to have opened a Pandora's Box that threatened to turn his realm into a parody of all he held dear".
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the last two of years of his life, Faisal fell into depression over the way his subjects had been seduced into a consumerist lifestyle, becoming lost in a sense of "melancholia".
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Faisal's son, Crown Prince Mohammad told Lacey in 1981: "The profligacy, the greed, he felt he could not stem it.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] He become so bound up in his work, there was almost nothing private of him left".
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A sign of the changed values was that despite the total ban on alcohol in Saudi Arabia, drinking and drug use became common with the younger members of the House of Saud.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] James Akins, the American ambassador in Riyadh reported; "the sky over Riyadh is black with vultures with new get-richer-quicker plans under their wings".
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1974, property prices in Riyadh doubled on a weekly basis for the entire year, as the prosperity led to a real estate speculation bubble that was often compared to the Klondike gold rush of 1898–1899.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] At the Red Sea port of Jeddah, there were so many ships queuing up laden with cement for the construction boom in Saudi Arabia, that construction contractors hired helicopters to fly the cement in, twenty bags per flight.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A number of families engaged in the Saudi construction industry such as the Juffali, Alireza, al-Khasshoggi and the bin Laden families all became very wealthy as a result of the construction boom.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The period after the oil shock of 1973–1974 is still fondly remembered in Saudi Arabia as the "age of abundance", where nearly everyone had a significant increase in their standard of living.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The wealth and corruption generated by the oil shock led to a fundamentalist backlash in Saudi Arabia.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On 20 November 1979, Islam's holiest shrine, the Grand Mosque of Mecca, was seized by a group who proclaimed themselves to be the followers of the Mahdi, a messianic figure said to appear at the dawn of every Muslim century to strike down the enemies of Islam.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The leader of the uprising, Juhayman al-Otaybi, read out a list of grievances, as he accused the House of Saud of being corrupt and degenerate, listing by name a number of Saudi princes who were engaged in dubious business dealings and/or who drank alcohol.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Saudi Army recaptured the Grand Mosque, and the surviving "renegades", as the rebels were labelled, were executed.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In Algeria, the "oil shock" led to the establishment of a welfare state where none had existed previously.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The lower oil prices of the 1980s along with cutbacks and the belief that the FLN regime was corrupt helped cause the riots of October 1988 against the FLN regime, that killed at least 500 people.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The riots were largely caused by the fact that the low oil prices had forced the Algerian state to end many of its more generous social policies between 1986 and 1988, leading to an unemployment rate of 30% by 1988, along with the knowledge that the FLN regime had stolen millions.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the aftermath of the October riots, President Chadli Bendjedid began a transition to democracy.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The first free elections in Algeria in January 1992 were won by the Islamist FIS, which led to a military coup and an outbreak of a civil war that killed hundreds of thousands of Algerians.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] OPEC-member states raised the prospect of nationalization of oil company holdings.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Most notably, Saudi Arabia nationalized Aramco in 1980 under the leadership of Saudi oil minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] As other OPEC nations followed suit, the cartel's income soared.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Saudi Arabia undertook a series of ambitious five-year development plans.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The biggest began in 1980, funded at $250 billion.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Other cartel members also undertook major economic development programs.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Control of oil became known as the "oil weapon".
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It came in the form of an embargo and production cutbacks from the Arab states.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The weapon was aimed at the United States, Great Britain, Canada, Japan and the Netherlands.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] These target governments perceived that the intent was to push them towards a more pro-Arab position.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] However, the affected countries did not undertake dramatic policy changes.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The risk that the Middle East could become another superpower confrontation with the USSR was of more concern to Washington than oil.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Further, interest groups and government agencies more worried about energy were no match for Kissinger's dominance.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The embargo had a negative influence on the US economy, causing immediate demands to address the threats to US energy security.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On an international level, the price increases changed competitive positions in many industries, such as automobiles.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Macroeconomic problems consisted of both inflationary and deflationary impacts.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The embargo left oil companies searching for new ways to increase oil supplies, even in rugged terrain such as the Arctic.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Finding oil and developing new fields usually required five to 10 years before significant production.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The average US retail price of a gallon of regular gasoline rose 43% from 38.5¢ in May 1973 to 55.1¢ in June 1974.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] State governments asked citizens not to put up Christmas lights.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Oregon banned Christmas and commercial lighting altogether.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Politicians called for a national gasoline rationing program.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Nixon asked gasoline retailers to voluntarily not sell gasoline on Saturday nights or Sundays.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] 90% of gas station owners complied, which produced long lines of motorists wanting to fill up their cars while they still could.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The "oil shock" provided considerable impetus to the American nuclear industry as a way to achieve "energy independence" from the Middle East.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On 7 November 1973, Nixon in an address to Congress called for Project Independence to make the United States self-sufficient in energy by 1980, which called for a massive investment in the nuclear industry.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Nixon envisioned nuclear energy as more economical, and was encouraged by the enthusiasm of many officials who saw nuclear energy as the technology of the future.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By the late 1960s, a lively environmentalist movement had emerged in the United States, and the Project Independence nuclear program was the subject of much debate in both the media and Congress.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The ensuing debates revealed that many of the claims made for nuclear power underestimated the true costs of nuclear reactors.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Equally problematic was where to safety store the spent nuclear rods that emitted a toxic level of radioactivity for centuries afterward, in a cost-effective manner.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The issue of the spent nuclear rods was especially difficult because of NIMBYism, where communities proved unwilling to accept a storage place for the inevitable by-product of nuclear power, the spent nuclear rods, with the demand that the government find some other community to store the rods.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Many of the nuclear reactors ordered in 1973 were cancelled due to cost overruns, while over 100 nuclear plants were shut down as uneconomical over the next 10 years.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Unlike nations that tried to use nuclear power as a way for energy independence such as France and Sweden, the United States had substantial reserves of its own oil, which weakened the case for nuclear power in the ensuring debates.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By 1989, only 18% of American energy came from nuclear power plants, which was a fraction of what Project Independence had envisioned in 1973.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil shock led to anti-Arab feelings becoming common.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Cartoons published in American newspapers during the oil shock depicted Arabs as disgusting, ugly, obese, corrupt and greedy.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the cartoons, the long hooked Semitic noses that had traditionally been featured in anti-Jewish cartoons were applied to the Arab sheiks as a way to illustrate their supposed greed.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] American public opinion did not see the use of the "oil weapon" as due to politics, and tended to explain the embargo as only due to the excessive greed of King Faisal and the other Arab leaders, hence the use of the hooked Semitic nose in the cartoons as a sort of shorthand for insatiable greed.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Soviet Union was not a beneficiary of the oil crisis.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The crisis prompted the USSR to raise energy prices within the Council on Mutual Economic Assistance (CMEA).
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The embargo was not uniform across Western Europe.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Of the nine members of the European Economic Community (EEC), the Netherlands faced a complete embargo.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By contrast Britain and France received almost uninterrupted supplies.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] That was their reward for refusing to allow the US to use their airfields and stopping arms and supplies to both the Arabs and the Israelis.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The other six EEC nations faced partial cutbacks.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The UK had traditionally been an ally of Israel, and Harold Wilson's government supported the Israelis during the Six-Day War.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] His successor, Ted Heath, reversed this policy in 1970, calling for Israel to withdraw to its pre-1967 borders.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The devalued franc made imports more expensive for French consumers, which encouraged them to buy French products, while making French products cheaper abroad.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] France was entirely dependent upon imported oil, through French companies continued to lease the oil concessions in Algeria until 1971.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The low price of oil internationally compensated to a certain extent for the higher price of oil caused by the devaluation.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The devalued franc ensured that the dramatic price increases caused by the oil shock hit the French economy especially hard in 1973.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The UK, Germany, Italy, Switzerland and Norway banned flying, driving and boating on Sundays.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Sweden rationed gasoline and heating oil.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Netherlands imposed prison sentences for those who used more than their ration of electricity.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The EEC was unable to achieve a common policy during the first month of the embargo.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It issued a statement on November 6, after the embargo and price rises had begun.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It was widely viewed as pro-Arab, supporting the Franco-British line on the war.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] OPEC duly lifted its embargo from all EEC members.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The other European states did not rally in defense of the Dutch who were left to fend for themselves and instead reached bilateral deals with Saudi Arabia, Iraq and Iran.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Faced with a recession, there was a tendency within the EEC nations to turn inwards away from European integration.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The price rises had a much greater impact in Europe than the embargo.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The crisis retarded the movement towards European economic integration which had been gathering pace ever since the EEC, now the European Union, had been founded in 1957.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1973, the German historian Jens-Uwe Wunderlich wrote that attempts to finish off the European common market came to a "complete standstill" in 1973 and it was not until 1977 that movement towards creating the common market resumed.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In particular, the oil shock increased the appeal of nuclear energy as a way to achieve energy independence from the turbulent Middle East.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Starting in March 1974 with the "Energy Plan" introduced by the premier Pierre Messmer, the French state made a massive investment in nuclear energy.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By the 1990s, 80% of all of France's energy came from nuclear plants.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The North Sea oil fields, which were discovered in 1969, did not start to be exploited until 1975, making the United Kingdom entirely dependent upon imported oil in 1973.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The way that world oil prices quadrupled in late 1973 had a very adverse impact on the British economy,.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In a series of speeches in December 1973, the Prime Minister Edward Heath warned that because of the oil shock that the British economy was going into recession and the British people should expect economic austerity.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Heath offered the coal miners a 7% wage increase, which was rejected as insufficient by the miners who went on strike.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Through not subjected to the embargo, the UK faced an energy crisis of its own—a series of strikes by coal miners and railroad workers over the winter of 1973–74 became a major factor in the defeat of Heath's Conservative government in the February 1974 general elections.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The new Labour government told the British to heat only one room in their houses over the winter.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Labour government of Harold Wilson settled the strike by giving the coal miners a 35% pay increase.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Japan was hard hit, since it imported 90% of its oil from the Middle East.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It had a stockpile good for 55 days, and another 20-day supply was en route.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Facing its most serious crisis since 1945, the government ordered a 10% cut in the consumption of industrial oil and electricity.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In December 1973, it ordered an immediate 20% cut in oil use and electric power to Japan's major industries, and cutbacks in leisure automobile usage.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Economist predicted the growth rate would plunge from 5% annually, down to zero or even negative territory.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Seeking to take advantage of the crisis, Japanese business called on the government to relax its controls on air pollution and water pollution.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Moscow tried to take advantage by promising energy assistance if Japan renounced its claim to the Kurile Islands.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Instead it made $3.3 billion of dollars in loans to the Arab states and called on Israel to step back.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Japan's defensive strategy was explained to Kissinger when he met with top leaders in Tokyo in November 1973.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the long run Japan never wavered in its determination to maintain very strong close ties to the United States, while in self-defense briefly providing the Arab powers with the rhetoric they demanded in return for resuming oil shipments in early 1974.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] To assure future oil flows, Japan added suppliers outside of the Middle East, invested in nuclear power, imposed conservation measures, and provided funding for Arab governments and the Palestinians.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The crisis was a major factor in the long-run shift of Japan's economy away from oil-intensive industries.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Japanese auto makers benefited from the crisis.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The jump in gasoline prices helped their small, fuel-efficient models to gain market share from the "gas-guzzling" Detroit competition.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] This triggered a drop in US sales of American cars that lasted into the 1980s.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil crisis contributed to the poor state of the Indian economy and played a role in Indira Gandhi's decision to impose The Emergency, a dictatorship.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The state led a push for coal as an energy source, even though there were reservations about its adverse environmental effects.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil shock destroyed the economy of South Vietnam.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A spokesman for President Nguyễn Văn Thiệu admitted in a TV interview that the government was being "overwhelmed" by the inflation caused by the oil shock.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] An American businessman living in Saigon stated after the oil shock, that attempting to make money in South Vietnam was "like making love to a corpse".
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In December 1973, Vietcong sappers attacked and destroyed the petroleum depot of Nha Be, further depleting fuel sources.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By the summer of 1974, the US embassy in Saigon reported that morale in the ARVN (Army of the Republic of Vietnam) had fallen to dangerously low levels and it was uncertain how much more longer South Vietnam would last.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] As inflation eroded the value of the South Vietnamese *đồng*, it became common by the summer of 1974 to see ARVN soldiers and their families begging in the streets for food.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In December 1974, the North Vietnamese PAVN (People's Army of Vietnam) launched an offensive in the Central Highlands that was far more successful than expected, due to the ARVN's low morale and weak resistance.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On March 1, 1975, the PAVN launched a major offensive that quickly overran the Central Highlands.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Following their victory in the Central Highlands, the North Vietnamese launched the "Ho Chi Minh Campaign" that captured Saigon on April 30, 1975.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Three of the nations targeted by the embargo were located in southern Africa or had colonies there.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Portugal which ruled the colonies of Angola, Portuguese Guiana (modern Guinea-Bissau), and Portuguese East Africa (modern Mozambique) had fighting colonial wars in all of its African colonies since the 1960s with Angola being the first to rise up in 1961.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Angola is rich in oil, which protected Portugal from the worse of the embargo.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] But the economic stability of the *Estado Novo* regime was damaged by the worldwide inflation, which help cause the Carnation Revolution which toppled the *Estado Novo* regime in April 1974 and led to the restoration of democracy.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Portugal granted independence to all of its colonies except for Macau in 1975.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The British historian Rob Skinner wrote the embargo had a "significant impact" on the South African economy.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The inflationary rise in commodity prices increased the input costs of South African manufacturing, making South African manufactured goods uncompetitive on the world market.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The rise in the price of gold as a hedge against inflation (South Africa has the world's largest gold mines) caused the *rand* to increase in value, which caused further problems for South African manufacturing.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The strategy pursued by the National Party government since 1948 of sponsoring the industrialization of South Africa was derailed by the oil shock, with what Skinner described as "important social and political consequences" for the *apartheid* regime.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Soweto uprising of 1976 was at least in part caused by anger at the high unemployment rate in the black South African community.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Even worse hit than South Africa was Rhodesia (modern Zimbabwe), where oil was already expensive as the white supremacist government of Rhodesia had been under United Nations sanctions since 1965, and thus the smugglers who sold Rhodesia oil charged a premium for their services.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The premium charged by the "sanctions busters" such as Iran increased after the embargo, which threw the Rhodesian economy into recession.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Despite the United Nations sanctions, Rhodesia was a major exporter of chrome, steel and tobacco with the United States exempting "strategical" Rhodesian products such as chrome from the sanctions.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The global recession of 1973–1975 proved more effective than the United Nations in ending the global demand for Rhodesian products, which made the Rhodesian recession especially severe.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Unlike South Africa, which had a sizable and long-standing white population, the white population of Rhodesia was much smaller and more recent.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Rhodesia depended considerably more than South Africa on white immigration to provide enough soldiers for its army, while most of the Rhodesian whites had only arrived in the 1950s and did not have very deep roots in the country.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The white flight caused by the recession put the Rhodesian Army at a major disadvantage in its war against the black guerrillas.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The war cost the Rhodesian government one million Rhodesian dollars per day by 1975, and the costs of the war threatened to bankrupt Rhodesia.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1979, Rhodesia signed the Lancaster House Agreement, which led to Black majority rule in 1980.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Price controls exacerbated the crisis in the US.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The system limited the price of "old oil", that which had already been discovered, while allowing newly discovered oil to be sold at a higher price, to encourage investment.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a result, old oil was withdrawn from the market, creating greater scarcity.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The rule also discouraged development of alternative energies.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The rule had been intended to promote oil exploration.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Scarcity was addressed by rationing, as in many countries.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Motorists faced long lines at gas stations beginning in summer 1972 and increasing by summer 1973.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A sign of the change caused by the crisis was that in 1974 the Exxon oil company replaced the General Motors corporation to be the largest corporation in the world, as measured by gross sales revenues.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Simon as the first Administrator of the Federal Energy Office, a short-term organization created to coordinate the response to the embargo.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Simon allocated states the same amount of domestic oil for 1974 that each had consumed in 1972, which worked for states whose populations were not increasing.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In other states, lines at gasoline stations were common.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The American Automobile Association reported that in the last week of February 1974, 20% of American gasoline stations had no fuel.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Odd–even rationing allowed vehicles with license plates having an odd number as the last digit, or a vanity license plate, to buy gas only on odd-numbered days of the month.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Others could buy only on even-numbered days.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In some states, a three-color flag system was used to denote gasoline availability at service stations—green for unrationed availability, yellow for restricted/rationed sales, and red for out of stock.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Rationing led to violent incidents, when truck drivers chose to strike for two days in December 1973 over the limited supplies that Simon had allocated for their industry.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In Pennsylvania and Ohio, non-striking truckers were shot at by striking truckers.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In Arkansas, trucks of non-strikers were attacked with bombs.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] America had controlled the price of natural gas since the 1950s.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] With the inflation of the 1970s, the price was too low to encourage the search for new reserves.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] America's natural gas reserves dwindled from 237 trillion in 1974 to 203 trillion in 1978.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The price controls were not changed, despite president Gerald Ford's repeated requests to Congress.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] To help reduce consumption, in 1974 a national maximum speed limit of 55 mph (89 km/h) was imposed through the Emergency Highway Energy Conservation Act.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Development of the Strategic Petroleum Reserve began in 1975, and in 1977 the cabinet-level Department of Energy was created, followed by the National Energy Act of 1978.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In November 1995, President Bill Clinton signed the National Highway Designation Act, ending the federal 55 mph speed limit, which allowed states to restore their prior maximum speed limit.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Year-round daylight saving time was implemented from January 6, 1974, to October 27, 1975, with a break between October 27, 1974, and February 23, 1975, when the country observed standard time.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Parents complained that it forced many children to travel to school before sunrise.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The crisis prompted a call to conserve energy, most notably a campaign by the Advertising Council using the tagline "Don't Be Fuelish".
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Many newspapers carried advertisements featuring cut-outs that could be attached to light switches, reading "Last Out, Lights Out: Don't Be Fuelish".
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Although not regulated by the new legislation, auto racing groups voluntarily began conserving.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1974, NASCAR reduced all race distances by 10%; the 24 Hours of Daytona and the 12 Hours of Sebring race were cancelled.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1975, the Energy Policy and Conservation Act was passed, leading to the creation of the Corporate Average Fuel Economy (CAFE) standards that required improved fuel economy for cars and light trucks.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1976, Congress created the Weatherization Assistance Program to help low-income homeowners and renters reduce their demand for heating and cooling through better insulation.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1980, domestic luxury cars with a 130-inch (3.3 m) wheelbase and gross weights averaging 4,500 pounds (2,041 kg) were no longer made.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The automakers had begun phasing out the traditional front engine/rear-wheel drive layout in compact cars in favor of lighter front engine/front-wheel drive designs.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A higher percentage of cars offered more efficient four-cylinder engines.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Domestic auto makers also began offering more fuel efficient diesel powered passenger cars as well.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The energy crisis led to greater interest in renewable energy, nuclear power and domestic fossil fuels.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 2013, Peter Grossman opined that American energy policies after the crisis became and remained dominated by crisis-mentality thinking, promoting expensive quick fixes and single-shot solutions that ignore market and technology realities.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] He wrote that instead of providing stable rules that support basic research while leaving plenty of scope for entrepreneurship and innovation, Congresses and presidents repeatedly backed policies which promised politically expedient solutions whose true prospects were doubtful.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The Brazilian government implemented its Proálcool (pro-alcohol) project in 1975 that mixed ethanol with gasoline for automotive fuel.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Israel was one of the few countries unaffected by the embargo, since it could extract sufficient oil from the Sinai.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] But to supplement Israel's over-taxed power grid, Harry Zvi Tabor, the father of Israel's solar industry, developed the prototype for a solar water heater now used in over 90% of Israeli homes.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Western central banks decided to sharply cut interest rates to encourage growth, deciding that inflation was a secondary concern.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Although this was the orthodox macroeconomic prescription at the time, the resulting stagflation surprised economists and central bankers.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The policy is now considered by some to have deepened and lengthened the adverse effects of the embargo.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Recent research claims that in the period after 1985 the economy became more resilient to energy price increases.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The price shock created large current account deficits in oil-importing economies.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A petrodollar recycling mechanism was created, through which OPEC surplus funds were channeled through the capital markets to the West to finance the current account deficits.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The functioning of this mechanism required the relaxation of capital controls in oil-importing economies.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] It marked the beginning of an exponential growth of Western capital markets.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In the United States in 1974, seven of the 15 top Fortune 500 companies were oil companies, falling to four in 2014.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The crisis had a major impact on international relations and created a rift within NATO.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Some European nations and Japan sought to disassociate themselves from United States foreign policy in the Middle East to avoid being targeted by the boycott.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Arab oil producers linked any future policy changes to peace between the belligerents.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] To address this, the Nixon Administration began multilateral negotiations with the combatants.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] They arranged for Israel to pull back from the Sinai Peninsula and the Golan Heights.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By January 18, 1974, US Secretary of State Henry Kissinger had negotiated an Israeli troop withdrawal from parts of the Sinai Peninsula.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The promise of a negotiated settlement between Israel and Syria was enough to convince Arab oil producers to lift the embargo in March 1974. and again during the 1979 energy crisis.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] America's Cold War policies suffered a major blow from the embargo.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] They had focused on China and the Soviet Union, but the latent challenge to US hegemony coming from the Third World became evident.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 2004, declassified documents revealed that the US was so distraught by the rise in oil prices and being challenged by underdeveloped countries that they briefly considered military action to forcibly seize Middle Eastern oilfields in late 1973.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Western Europe began switching from pro-Israel to more pro-Arab policies.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] This change strained the Western alliance.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The US, which imported only 12% of its oil from the Middle East (compared with 80% for the Europeans and over 90% for Japan), remained staunchly committed to Israel.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The percentage of US oil which comes from the nations bordering the Persian Gulf remained steady over the decades, with a figure of a little more than 10% in 2008.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] With the embargo in place, many developed countries altered their policies regarding the Arab-Israeli conflict.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] These included the UK, which refused to allow the United States to use British bases and Cyprus to airlift resupplies to Israel, along with the rest of the members of the European Community.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Canada shifted towards a more pro-Arab position after displeasure was expressed towards Canada's mostly neutral position.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] "On the other hand, after the embargo the Canadian government moved quickly indeed toward the Arab position, despite its low dependence on Middle Eastern oil".
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Although lacking historical connections to the Middle East, Japan was the country most dependent on Arab oil.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] 71% of its imported oil came from the Middle East in 1970.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] On November 7, 1973, the Saudi and Kuwaiti governments declared Japan a "nonfriendly" country, to encourage it to change its noninvolvement policy.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] It received a 5% production cut in December, causing a panic.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] On November 22, Japan issued a statement "asserting that Israel should withdraw from all of the 1967 territories, advocating Palestinian self-determination, and threatening to reconsider its policy toward Israel if Israel refused to accept these preconditions".
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By December 25, Japan was considered an Arab-friendly state.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil embargo was announced roughly one month after a right-wing military coup in Chile led by General Augusto Pinochet toppled socialist president Salvador Allende on September 11, 1973.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The response of the Nixon administration was to propose doubling arms sales.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a consequence, an opposing Latin American bloc was organized and financed in part by Venezuelan oil revenues, which quadrupled between 1970 and 1975.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil shock disrupted the status quo relationships between Arab countries and the US and USSR.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] At the time, Egypt, Syria and Iraq were allied with the USSR.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia, Turkey and Iran, plus Israel, aligned with the US.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Vacillations in alignment often resulted in greater support from the respective superpowers.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] When Anwar Sadat became president of Egypt in 1970, he dismissed Soviet specialists in Egypt and reoriented towards the US.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Concerns over economic domination from increased Soviet oil production turned into fears of military aggression after the 1979 Soviet invasion of Afghanistan, a major turning point in Cold War geopolitics.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Persian Gulf states turned toward the US for security guarantees against Soviet military action, coming at a time marked by increased American weapons sales, technology, and outright military presence to various US-allied nations.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia and Iran became increasingly dependent on American security assurances to manage both external and internal threats, including increased military competition between them over increased oil revenues.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Both states were competing for preeminence in the Persian Gulf, and using increased revenues to fund expanded militaries.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1979, Saudi arms purchases from the US were five times larger than Israel's.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia is a near-absolute monarchy, an Arabic speaking country, and has a Sunni Muslim majority, while Persian speaking Iran since 1979 is an Islamist theocracy with a Shiite Muslim majority, which explains the current hostility between Saudi Arabia and Iran.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil crisis sent a signal to the auto industry globally, which changed many aspects of production and usage for decades to come.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] After World War II, most West European countries taxed motor fuel to limit imports, and as a result most cars made in Europe were smaller and more economical than their American counterparts.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By the late 1960s, increasing incomes supported rising car sizes.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil crisis pushed West European car buyers away from larger, less economical cars.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The most notable result of this transition was the rise in popularity of compact hatchbacks.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The only notable small hatchbacks built in Western Europe before the oil crisis were the Peugeot 104, Renault 5 and Fiat 127.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By the end of the decade, the market had expanded with the introduction of the Ford Fiesta, Opel Kadett (sold as the Vauxhall Astra in Great Britain), Chrysler Sunbeam and Citroën Visa.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Buyers looking for larger cars were increasingly drawn to medium-sized hatchbacks.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Virtually unknown in Europe in 1973, by the end of the decade they were gradually replacing sedans as the mainstay of this sector.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Between 1973 and 1980, medium-sized hatchbacks were launched across Europe: the Chrysler/Simca Horizon, Fiat Ritmo (Strada in the UK), Ford Escort MK3, Renault 14, Volvo 340 / 360, Opel Kadett, and Volkswagen Golf.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] These cars were considerably more economical than the traditional saloons they were replacing, and attracted buyers who traditionally bought larger vehicles.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Some 15 years after the oil crisis, hatchbacks dominated most European small and medium car markets, and had gained a substantial share of the large family car market.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Before the energy crisis, large, heavy, and powerful cars were popular.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1971, the standard engine in a Chevrolet Caprice was a 400-cubic inch (6.5 liter) V8.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The wheelbase of this car was 121.5 inches (3,090 mm), and *Motor Trend*'s 1972 road test of the similar Chevrolet Impala achieved no more than 15 highway miles per gallon.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In the 15 years prior to the 1973 oil crisis, gasoline prices in the US had lagged well behind inflation.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The crisis reduced the demand for large cars.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Japanese imports became mass-market leaders with unibody construction and front-wheel drive, which became de facto standards.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] From Europe, the Volkswagen Beetle, the Volkswagen Fastback, the Renault 8, the Renault LeCar, and the Fiat Brava were successful.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Detroit responded with the Ford Pinto, the Ford Maverick, the Chevrolet Vega, the Chevrolet Nova, the Plymouth Valiant and the Plymouth Volaré.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] American Motors sold its homegrown Gremlin, Hornet and Pacer models.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A decade after the 1973 oil crisis, Honda, Toyota and Nissan, affected by the 1981 voluntary export restraints, opened US assembly plants and established their luxury divisions (Acura, Lexus and Infiniti, respectively) to distinguish themselves from their mass-market brands.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Compact trucks were introduced, such as the Toyota Hilux and the Datsun Truck, followed by the Mazda Truck (sold as the Ford Courier), and the Isuzu-built Chevrolet LUV.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Mitsubishi rebranded its Forte as the Dodge D-50 a few years after the oil crisis.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Mazda, Mitsubishi and Isuzu had joint partnerships with Ford, Chrysler, and GM, respectively.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Later, the American makers introduced their domestic replacements (Ford Ranger, Dodge Dakota and the Chevrolet S10/GMC S-15), ending their captive import policy.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] An increase in imported cars into North America forced General Motors, Ford and Chrysler to introduce smaller and fuel-efficient models for domestic sales.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The Dodge Omni / Plymouth Horizon from Chrysler, the Ford Fiesta and the Chevrolet Chevette all had four-cylinder engines and room for at least four passengers by the late 1970s.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1985, the average American vehicle moved 17.4 miles per gallon, compared to 13.5 in 1970.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The improvements stayed, even though the price of a barrel of oil remained constant at $12 from 1974 to 1979.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Sales of large sedans for most makes, except Chrysler products, recovered within two model years of the 1973 crisis.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The Cadillac DeVille and Fleetwood, Buick Electra, Oldsmobile 98, Lincoln Continental, Mercury Marquis, and various other luxury oriented sedans became popular again in the mid-1970s.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The only full-size models that did not recover were lower price models such as the Chevrolet Bel Air and Ford Galaxie 500.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Slightly smaller models such as the Oldsmobile Cutlass, Chevrolet Monte Carlo, Ford Thunderbird and various others sold well.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Economical imports succeeded alongside heavy, expensive vehicles.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1976, Toyota sold 346,920 cars (average weight around 2,100 lbs), while Cadillac sold 309,139 cars (average weight around 5,000 lbs).
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Federal safety standards, such as NHTSA Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standard 215 (pertaining to safety bumpers), and compacts like the 1974 Mustang I were a prelude to the DOT "downsize" revision of vehicle categories.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1977, GM's full-sized cars reflected the crisis.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1979, virtually all "full-size" American cars had shrunk, featuring smaller engines and smaller outside dimensions.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Chrysler ended production of their full-sized luxury sedans at the end of the 1981 model year, moving instead to a full front-wheel drive lineup for 1982, except for the M-body Dodge Diplomat/Plymouth Gran Fury and Chrysler New Yorker Fifth Avenue sedans.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] OPEC soon lost its preeminent position, and in 1981, its production was surpassed by that of other countries.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Additionally, its own member nations were divided.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia, trying to recover market share, increased production, pushing prices down, shrinking or eliminating profits for high-cost producers.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The world price, which had peaked during the 1979 energy crisis at nearly $40 per barrel, decreased during the 1980s to less than $10 per barrel.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Adjusted for inflation, oil briefly fell back to pre-1973 levels.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] This "sale" price was a windfall for oil-importing nations, both developing and developed.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] During the Iran–Iraq War of 1980–1988, the stated war aim of Iran was to overthrow the Baath regime in Iraq.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a consequence, Saudi Arabia and the other Arab Gulf states leaned in a very pro-Iraqi neutrality during the war.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a part of its policy of supporting Iraq, Saudi Arabia pumped out oil in massive quantities to lower the price as a way of hurting Iran's economy.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The low price of oil also hurt Iraq's economy, which forced Iraq to borrow massive sums of money, putting Iraq deeply into debt.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In contrast, Iran refused to borrow any money because of its refusal to pay interest on any loans, and paid the costs of the war directly from the sale of its oil.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Iran's revenue from the sale of oil went from $20 billion US dollars per year in 1982 to $5 billion US dollars per year by 1988, which pushed Iran to the verge of bankruptcy and forced Iran to make peace with Iraq later in 1988.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] During the war, the Iranian delegation at OPEC tried very hard to have the group cut production to raise prices, but were blocked by the other delegations led by the Saudi delegation, who insisted on more oil production.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The embargo encouraged new venues for energy exploration, including Alaska, the North Sea, the Caspian Sea, and the Caucasus.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Exploration in the Caspian Basin and Siberia became profitable.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Cooperation changed into a far more adversarial relationship as the USSR increased its production.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1980, the Soviet Union had become the world's largest producer.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Part of the decline in prices and economic and geopolitical power of OPEC came from the move to alternative energy sources.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] OPEC had relied on price inelasticity to maintain high consumption, but had underestimated the extent to which conservation and other sources of supply would eventually reduce demand.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Electricity generation from nuclear power and natural gas, home heating from natural gas, and ethanol-blended gasoline all reduced the demand for oil.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The drop in prices presented a serious problem for oil-exporting countries in northern Europe and the Persian Gulf.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Heavily populated, impoverished countries, whose economies were largely dependent on oil—including Mexico, Nigeria, Algeria, and Libya—did not prepare for a market reversal that left them in sometimes desperate situations.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] When reduced demand and increased production glutted the world market in the mid-1980s, oil prices plummeted and the cartel lost its unity.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Mexico (a non-member), Nigeria, and Venezuela, whose economies had expanded in the 1970s, faced near-bankruptcy, and even Saudi Arabian economic power was significantly weakened.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The divisions within OPEC made concerted action more difficult.
[src:gasoline/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As of 2015, OPEC has never approached its earlier dominance.
[src:gasoline/2-2-4-trimethylpentane] Strictly speaking, if the standard meaning of "iso" is followed, the name *isooctane* should be reserved for the isomer 2-methylheptane.
[src:gasoline/2-2-4-trimethylpentane] However, 2,2,4-trimethylpentane is by far the most important isomer of octane and historically it has been assigned this name.
[src:gasoline/2-2-4-trimethylpentane] Isooctane is produced on a massive scale in the petroleum industry by alkylation of isobutene with isobutane.
[src:gasoline/2-2-4-trimethylpentane] This process is conducted in alkylation units in the presence of acid catalysts.
[src:gasoline/2-2-4-trimethylpentane] It can also be produced from isobutylene by dimerization using an Amberlyst catalyst to produce a mixture of iso-octenes.
[src:gasoline/2-2-4-trimethylpentane] Hydrogenation of this mixture produces 2,2,4-trimethylpentane.
[src:gasoline/2-2-4-trimethylpentane] Engine knocking is an unwanted process that can occur during high compression ratios in internal combustion engines.
[src:gasoline/2-2-4-trimethylpentane] During the 1920s different measurement methods of knock were proposed but laboratories struggled to reproduce them reliably.
[src:gasoline/2-2-4-trimethylpentane] In 1926 Ethyl Corporation's Graham Edgar selected two specific hydrocarbons, *n*-heptane (commercially available in high purity from Jeffrey pine) and 2,2,4-trimethylpentane, itself first synthesized from tert-butyl alcohol via diisobutene by J.
[src:gasoline/2-2-4-trimethylpentane] McKinney at the same laboratory in the same year, as primary standards.
[src:gasoline/2-2-4-trimethylpentane] Compared to various chemicals and natural gasolines proposed before that, these two compounds had extremely close boiling points, ensuring the vapor mixture in the cylinder would be the same regardless of the carburetor, and didn't depend on the composition of particular crudes.
[src:gasoline/2-2-4-trimethylpentane] This method became known as the octane rating scale.
[src:gasoline/2-2-4-trimethylpentane] Test motors using 2,2,4-trimethylpentane gave a certain performance that was standardized as 100 octane.
[src:gasoline/2-2-4-trimethylpentane] The same test motors, run in the same fashion, using heptane, gave a performance which was standardized as 0 octane.
[src:gasoline/2-2-4-trimethylpentane] All other fuels were then graded against mixtures of these two chemicals and assigned octane numbers.
[src:gasoline/2-2-4-trimethylpentane] In common with all hydrocarbons, 2,2,4-trimethylpentane is flammable.
[src:gasoline/2-4-dimethyl-6-tert-butylphenol] It is used as an antioxidant, e.g. to prevent gumming in fuels, and as an ultraviolet stabilizer.
[src:gasoline/2-4-dimethyl-6-tert-butylphenol] It is used in jet fuels, gasolines, and avgas.
[src:gasoline/2-4-dimethyl-6-tert-butylphenol] It is prepared by alkylation of xylenol with isobutylene.
[src:gasoline/2-4-dimethyl-6-tert-butylphenol] This alkylation provides a means to separate 2,4-xylenol from 2,5-xylenol since 2,4-dimethyl-6-tert-butylphenol is insoluble in 10% NaOH but 2,5-dimethyl-6-tert-butylphenol is soluble.
[src:gasoline/2-4-dimethyl-6-tert-butylphenol] Subsequent to separation, the tert-butyl group can be removed in strong acid.
[src:gasoline/2-4-dimethyl-6-tert-butylphenol] One of its trade names is **Topanol A**.
[src:gasoline/2-4-dimethyl-6-tert-butylphenol] It is found in antioxidant mixtures AO-30, AO-31, AO-32, IONOL K72, IONOL K78, IONOL K98, and others.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The ability of a particular gasoline blend to resist premature ignition (which causes knocking and reduces efficiency in reciprocating engines) is measured by its octane rating or performance number.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Tetraethyl lead was once widely used to increase the octane rating but is not used in modern automotive gasoline due to the health hazard.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Aviation, off-road motor vehicles, and some racing car engines still use leaded gasolines.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Other substances are frequently added to gasoline to improve chemical stability and performance characteristics, control corrosion, and provide fuel system cleaning.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Gasoline may contain oxygen-containing chemicals such as ethanol, MTBE, or ETBE to improve combustion.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] English dictionaries show that the term *gasoline* originates from *gas* plus the chemical suffixes *-ole* and *-ine*.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] *Petrol* derives from the Medieval Latin word *petroleum* (L.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Interest in gasoline-like fuels started with the invention of internal combustion engines suitable for use in transportation applications.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The so-called Otto engines were developed in Germany during the last quarter of the 19th century.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The fuel for these early engines was a relatively volatile hydrocarbon obtained from coal gas.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] With a boiling point near 85 °C (185 °F) (*n*-octane boils at 125.62 °C (258.12 °F)), it was well suited for early carburettors (evaporators).
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The development of a "spray nozzle" carburettor enabled the use of less volatile fuels.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Further improvements in engine efficiency were attempted at higher compression ratios, but early attempts were blocked by the premature explosion of fuel, known as knocking.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] In 1891, the Shukhov cracking process became the world's first commercial method to break down heavier hydrocarbons in crude oil to increase the percentage of lighter products compared to simple distillation.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Commercial gasoline, as well as other liquid transportation fuels, are complex mixtures of hydrocarbons.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The performance specification also varies with season, requiring less volatile blends during summer, in order to minimize evaporative losses.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Roughly 72 liters (19 U.S. gal) of gasoline is derived from a 160-liter (42 U.S. gal) barrel of crude oil.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Material separated from crude oil via distillation, called virgin or straight-run gasoline, does not meet specifications for modern engines, particularly the octane rating; see below, but can be pooled to the gasoline blend.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The bulk of a typical gasoline consists of a homogeneous mixture of hydrocarbons with between four and twelve carbon atoms per molecule, commonly referred to as C4–C12.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] It is a mixture of paraffins (alkanes), olefins (alkenes), naphthenes (cycloalkanes), and aromatics.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The use of the term *paraffin* in place of the standard chemical nomenclature *alkane* is particular to the oil industry, which relies extensively on jargon.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The various refinery streams blended to make gasoline have different characteristics.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The terms above are the jargon used in the oil industry, and the terminology varies.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Many countries set limits on gasoline aromatics in general, benzene in particular, and olefin (alkene) content.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Such regulations have led to an increasing preference for alkane isomers, such as isomerate or alkylate, as their octane rating is higher than n-alkanes.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] In the European Union, the benzene limit is set at one percent by volume for all grades of automotive gasoline.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] This is usually achieved by avoiding feeding C6, in particular cyclohexane, to the reformer unit, where it would be converted to benzene.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Therefore, only (desulfurized) heavy virgin naphtha (HVN) is fed to the reformer unit.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Gasoline can also contain other organic compounds, such as organic ethers, deliberately added, plus small levels of contaminants, in particular organosulfur compounds, which are usually removed at the refinery.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] On average, U.S. petroleum refineries produce about 19 to 20 gallons of gasoline, 11 to 13 gallons of distillate fuel diesel fuel and 3 to 4 gallons of jet fuel from each 42 U.S. gallons (160 liters) barrel of crude oil.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The product ratio depends upon the processing in an oil refinery and the crude oil assay.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The specific gravity of gasoline ranges from 0.71 to 0.77, with higher densities having a greater volume fraction of aromatics.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Finished marketable gasoline is traded (in Europe) with a standard reference of 0.755 kilograms per liter (6.30 lb/U.S. gal), (7,5668 lb/ imp gal).
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Its price is escalated or de-escalated according to its actual density.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Because of its low density, gasoline floats on water, and therefore water cannot generally be used to extinguish a gasoline fire unless applied in a fine mist.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Quality gasoline should be stable for six months if stored properly, but can degrade over time.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Gasoline stored for a year will most likely be able to be burned in an internal combustion engine without too much trouble.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] When gasoline is not stored correctly, gums and solids may result, which can corrode system components and accumulate on wet surfaces, resulting in a condition called "stale fuel".
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Gasoline containing ethanol is especially subject to absorbing atmospheric moisture, then forming gums, solids, or two phases (a hydrocarbon phase floating on top of a water-alcohol phase).
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The presence of these degradation products in the fuel tank or fuel lines plus a carburettor or fuel injection components makes it harder to start the engine, or causes reduced engine performance.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] On resumption of regular engine use, the buildup may or may not be eventually cleaned out by the flow of fresh gasoline.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The addition of a fuel stabilizer to gasoline can extend the life of fuel that is not or cannot be stored properly.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Removal of all fuel from a fuel system is the only real solution to the problem of long-term storage of an engine or a machine or vehicle.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Typical fuel stabilizers are proprietary mixtures containing mineral spirits, isopropyl alcohol, 1,2,4-trimethylbenzene or other additives.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Fuel stabilizers are commonly used for small engines, such as lawnmower and tractor engines, especially when their use is sporadic or seasonal (little to no use for one or more seasons of the year).
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Gasoline stability requirements are set by the standard ASTM D4814.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] This standard describes the various characteristics and requirements of automotive fuels for use over a wide range of operating conditions in ground vehicles equipped with spark-ignition engines.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] A gasoline-fueled internal combustion engine obtains energy from the combustion of gasoline's various hydrocarbons with oxygen from the ambient air, yielding carbon dioxide and water as exhaust.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] By weight, combustion of gasoline releases about 46.7 megajoules per kilogram (13.0 kWh/kg; 21.2 MJ/lb) or by volume 33.6 megajoules per liter (9.3 kWh/L; 127 MJ/U.S. gal; 121,000 BTU/U.S. gal), quoting the lower heating value.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Gasoline blends differ, and therefore actual energy content varies according to the season and producer by up to 1.75 percent more or less than the average.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] On average, about 74 liters (20 U.S. gal) of gasoline are available from a barrel of crude oil (about 46 percent by volume), varying with the quality of the crude and the grade of the gasoline.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The remainder is products ranging from tar to naphtha.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] A high-octane-rated fuel, such as liquefied petroleum gas (LPG), has an overall lower power output at the typical 10:1 compression ratio of an engine design optimized for gasoline fuel.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] An engine tuned for LPG fuel via higher compression ratios (typically 12:1) improves the power output.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] This is because higher-octane fuels allow for a higher compression ratio without knocking, resulting in a higher cylinder temperature, which improves efficiency.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Increased mechanical efficiency is created by a higher compression ratio through the concomitant higher expansion ratio on the power stroke, which is by far the greater effect.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The higher expansion ratio extracts more work from the high-pressure gas created by the combustion process.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] An Atkinson cycle engine uses the timing of the valve events to produce the benefits of a high expansion ratio without the disadvantages, chiefly detonation, of a high compression ratio.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] A high expansion ratio is also one of the two key reasons for the efficiency of diesel engines, along with the elimination of pumping losses due to throttling of the intake airflow.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The lower energy content of LPG by liquid volume in comparison to gasoline is due mainly to its lower density.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] This lower density is a property of the lower molecular weight of propane (LPG's chief component) compared to gasoline's blend of various hydrocarbon compounds with heavier molecular weights than propane.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Conversely, LPG's energy content by weight is higher than gasoline's due to a higher hydrogen-to-carbon ratio.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Octane rating is measured relative to a mixture of 2,2,4-trimethylpentane (an isomer of octane) and n-heptane.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] There are different conventions for expressing octane ratings, so the same physical fuel may have several different octane ratings based on the measure used.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] One of the best known is the research octane number (RON).
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The octane rating of typical commercially available gasoline varies by country.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] In Finland, Sweden, and Norway, 95 RON is the standard for regular unleaded gasoline and 98 RON is also available as a more expensive option.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] In the United Kingdom, over 95 percent of gasoline sold has 95 RON and is marketed as Unleaded or Premium Unleaded.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Super Unleaded, with 97/98 RON and branded high-performance fuels (e.g., Shell V-Power, BP Ultimate) with 99 RON make up the balance.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Gasoline with 102 RON may rarely be available for racing purposes.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] In the U.S., octane ratings in unleaded fuels vary between 85 and 87 AKI (91–92 RON) for regular, 89–90 AKI (94–95 RON) for mid-grade (equivalent to European regular), up to 90–94 AKI (95–99 RON) for premium (European premium).
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Octane rating became important as the military sought higher output for aircraft engines in the late 1920s and the 1940s.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] A higher octane rating allows a higher compression ratio or supercharger boost, and thus higher temperatures and pressures, which translate to higher power output.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Some scientists even predicted that a nation with a good supply of high-octane gasoline would have the advantage in air power.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] In 1943, the Rolls-Royce Merlin aero engine produced 980 kilowatts (1,320 hp) using 100 RON fuel from a modest 27 liters (1,600 cu in) displacement.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] By the time of Operation Overlord, both the RAF and USAAF were conducting some operations in Europe using 150 RON fuel (100/150 avgas), obtained by adding 2.5 percent aniline to 100-octane avgas.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] By this time, the Rolls-Royce Merlin 66 was developing 1,500 kilowatts (2,000 hp) using this fuel.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Gasoline, when used in high-compression internal combustion engines, tends to auto-ignite or "detonate" causing damaging engine knocking, also called "pinging" or "pinking".
[src:gasoline/gasoline] To address this problem, tetraethyl lead (TEL) was widely adopted as an additive for gasoline in the 1920s.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] With a growing awareness of the seriousness of the extent of environmental and health damage caused by lead compounds, and the incompatibility of lead with catalytic converters, governments began to mandate reductions in gasoline lead.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] In the U.S., the Environmental Protection Agency issued regulations to reduce the lead content of leaded gasoline over a series of annual phases, scheduled to begin in 1973 but delayed by court appeals until 1976.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] By 1995, leaded fuel accounted for only 0.6 percent of total gasoline sales and under 1,800 metric tons (2,000 short tons; 1,800 long tons) of lead per year.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Clean Air Act banned the sale of leaded fuel for use in on-road vehicles in the U.S.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The use of TEL also necessitated other additives, such as dibromoethane.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] European countries began replacing lead-containing additives at the end of the 1980s.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] By the end of the 1990s, leaded gasoline was banned within the entire European Union with an exception for Avgas 100LL for general aviation.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The UAE started to switch to unleaded in the early 2000s.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Reduction in the average lead content of human blood may be a major cause for falling violent crime rates around the world including South Africa.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] A study found a correlation between leaded gasoline usage and violent crime (see Lead–crime hypothesis).
[src:gasoline/gasoline] In August 2021, the UN Environment Programme announced that leaded gasoline had been eradicated worldwide, with Algeria being the last country to deplete its reserves.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] UN Secretary-General António Guterres called the eradication of leaded petrol an "international success story".
[src:gasoline/gasoline] He also added: "Ending the use of leaded petrol will prevent more than one million premature deaths each year from heart disease, strokes and cancer, and it will protect children whose IQs are damaged by exposure to lead".
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Greenpeace called the announcement "the end of one toxic era".
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Leaded gasoline continues to be used in aeronautic, auto racing, and off-road applications.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The use of leaded additives is still permitted worldwide for the formulation of some grades of aviation gasoline such as 100LL, because the required octane rating is difficult to reach without the use of leaded additives.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Different additives have replaced lead compounds.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The most popular additives include aromatic hydrocarbons, ethers (MTBE and ETBE), and alcohols, most commonly ethanol.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Lead replacement petrol (LRP) was developed for vehicles designed to run on leaded fuels and incompatible with unleaded fuels.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Rather than tetraethyllead, it contains other metals such as potassium compounds or methylcyclopentadienyl manganese tricarbonyl (MMT); these are purported to buffer soft exhaust valves and seats so that they do not suffer recession due to the use of unleaded fuel.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] LRP was marketed during and after the phaseout of leaded motor fuels in the United Kingdom, Australia, South Africa, and some other countries.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Consumer confusion led to a widespread mistaken preference for LRP rather than unleaded, and LRP was phased out 8 to 10 years after the introduction of unleaded.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Leaded gasoline was withdrawn from sale in Britain after 31 December 1999, seven years after EEC regulations signalled the end of production for cars using leaded gasoline in member states.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] At this stage, a large percentage of cars from the 1980s and early 1990s which ran on leaded gasoline were still in use, along with cars that could run on unleaded fuel.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The declining number of such cars on British roads saw many gasoline stations withdrawing LRP from sale by 2003.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Methylcyclopentadienyl manganese tricarbonyl (MMT) is used in Canada and the U.S. to boost octane rating.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Its use in the U.S. has been restricted by regulations, although it is currently allowed.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Its use in the European Union is restricted by Article 8a of the Fuel Quality Directive following its testing under the Protocol for the evaluation of effects of metallic fuel-additives on the emissions performance of vehicles.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Gummy, sticky resin deposits result from oxidative degradation of gasoline during long-term storage.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] These harmful deposits arise from the oxidation of alkenes and other minor components in gasoline (see drying oils).
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Improvements in refinery techniques have generally reduced the susceptibility of gasolines to these problems.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Previously, catalytically or thermally cracked gasolines were most susceptible to oxidation.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The formation of gums is accelerated by copper salts, which can be neutralized by additives called metal deactivators.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] This degradation can be prevented through the addition of 5–100 ppm of antioxidants, such as phenylenediamines and other amines.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Hydrocarbons with a bromine number of 10 or above can be protected with the combination of unhindered or partially hindered phenols and oil-soluble strong amine bases, such as hindered phenols.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] "Stale" gasoline can be detected by a colorimetric enzymatic test for organic peroxides produced by oxidation of the gasoline.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Gasolines are also treated with metal deactivators, which are compounds that sequester (deactivate) metal salts that otherwise accelerate the formation of gummy residues.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The metal impurities might arise from the engine itself or as contaminants in the fuel.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Gasoline, as delivered at the pump, also contains additives to reduce internal engine carbon buildup, improve combustion and allow easier starting in cold climates.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] High levels of detergent can be found in Top Tier Detergent Gasolines.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The specification for Top Tier Detergent Gasolines was developed by four automakers: GM, Honda, Toyota, and BMW.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] According to the bulletin, the minimal U.S.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] EPA requirement is not sufficient to keep engines clean.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Typical detergents include alkylamines and alkyl phosphates at a level of 50–100 ppm.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] In the EU, 5 percent ethanol can be added within the common gasoline spec (EN 228).
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Discussions are ongoing to allow 10 percent blending of ethanol, available in Finnish, French and German gasoline stations.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] In Finland, most gasoline stations sell 95E10, which is 10 percent ethanol, and 98E5, which is 5 percent ethanol.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Most gasoline sold in Sweden has 5–15 percent ethanol added.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Three different ethanol blends are sold in the Netherlands—E5, E10 and hE15.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The last of these differs from standard ethanol–gasoline blends in that it consists of 15 percent hydrous ethanol (i.e., the ethanol–water azeotrope) instead of the anhydrous ethanol traditionally used for blending with gasoline.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] From 2009 to 2022, renewable percentage in gasoline slowly increased from 5% to 10%, even though EU-produced ethanol can achieve a climate-neutral production capability and most EU cars can use E10.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] E10 availability is low even in larger countries like Germany (26%) and France (58%).
[src:gasoline/gasoline] 8 countries in the EU have not adopted E10 as of 2024.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The Brazilian National Agency of Petroleum, Natural Gas and Biofuels (ANP) requires gasoline for automobile use to have 27.5 percent of ethanol added to its composition.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Pure hydrated ethanol is also available as a fuel.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Australia uses E10 (up to 10% ethanol) and E85 (up to 85% ethanol) in its gasoline.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] New South Wales mandated biofuel in its Biofuels Act 2007, and Queensland had a biofuel mandate since 2017.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Fuel pumps must be clearly labelled with its ethanol/biodiesel content.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The federal Renewable Fuel Standard (RFS) effectively requires refiners and blenders to blend renewable biofuels (mostly ethanol) with gasoline, sufficient to meet a growing annual target of total gallons blended.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Although the mandate does not require a specific percentage of ethanol, annual increases in the target combined with declining gasoline consumption have caused the typical ethanol content in gasoline to approach 10 percent.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Most fuel pumps display a sticker that states that the fuel may contain up to 10 percent ethanol, an intentional disparity that reflects the varying actual percentage.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] In parts of the U.S., ethanol is sometimes added to gasoline without an indication that it is a component.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] In October 2007, the Government of India decided to make five percent ethanol blending (with gasoline) mandatory.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Currently, 10 percent ethanol blended product (E10) is being sold in parts of the country.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Ethanol has been found in at least one study to damage catalytic converters.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] In July, 2025, India has mandated blending of E20 despite facing backlash.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Though gasoline is a naturally colourless liquid, many gasolines are dyed in various colours to indicate their composition and acceptable uses.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] In Australia, the lowest grade of gasoline (RON 91) was dyed a light shade of red/orange, but is now the same colour as the medium grade (RON 95) and high octane (RON 98), which are dyed yellow.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] In the U.S., aviation gasoline (avgas) is dyed to identify its octane rating and to distinguish it from kerosene-based jet fuel, which is left colourless.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] In Canada, the gasoline for marine and farm use is dyed red and is not subject to fuel excise tax in most provinces.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Oxygenate blending adds oxygen-bearing compounds such as methanol, MTBE, ETBE, TAME, TAEE, ethanol, and biobutanol.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The presence of these oxygenates reduces the amount of carbon monoxide and unburned fuel in the exhaust.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] In many areas throughout the U.S., oxygenate blending is mandated by EPA regulations to reduce smog and other airborne pollutants.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] For example, in Southern California fuel must contain two percent oxygen by weight, resulting in a mixture of 5.6 percent ethanol in gasoline.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The resulting fuel is often known as reformulated gasoline (RFG) or oxygenated gasoline, or, in the case of California, California reformulated gasoline (CARBOB).
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The federal requirement that RFG contain oxygen was dropped in May 2006 because the industry had developed VOC-controlled RFG that did not need additional oxygen.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] MTBE was phased out in the U.S. due to groundwater contamination and the resulting regulations and lawsuits.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Ethanol and, to a lesser extent, ethanol-derived ETBE are common substitutes.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] A common ethanol-gasoline mix of 10 percent ethanol mixed with gasoline is called gasohol or E10, and an ethanol-gasoline mix of 85 percent ethanol mixed with gasoline is called E85.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The most extensive use of ethanol takes place in Brazil, where the ethanol is derived from sugarcane.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] In 2004, over 13 billion liters (3.4×10^9 U.S. gal) of ethanol was produced in the U.S. for fuel use, mostly from corn and sold as E10.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] E85 is slowly becoming available in much of the U.S., though many of the relatively few stations vending E85 are not open to the general public.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The use of bioethanol and bio-methanol, either directly or indirectly by conversion of ethanol to bio-ETBE, or methanol to bio-MTBE is encouraged by the European Union Directive on the Promotion of the use of biofuels and other renewable fuels for transport.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Since producing bioethanol from fermented sugars and starches involves distillation, though, ordinary people in much of Europe cannot legally ferment and distill their own bioethanol at present (unlike in the U.S., where getting a BATF distillation permit has been easy since the 1973 oil crisis).
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Hydrocarbons in gasoline generally exhibit low acute toxicities, with LD50 of 700–2700 mg/kg for simple aromatic compounds.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Benzene and many anti-knocking additives are carcinogenic.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] People can be exposed to gasoline in the workplace by swallowing it, breathing in vapours, skin contact, and eye contact.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health (NIOSH) has also designated gasoline as a carcinogen.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Physical contact, ingestion, or inhalation can cause health problems.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Since ingesting large amounts of gasoline can cause permanent damage to major organs, a call to a local poison control centre or emergency room visit is indicated.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Contrary to common misconception, swallowing gasoline does not generally require special emergency treatment, and inducing vomiting does not help, and can make it worse.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] According to poison specialist Brad Dahl, "even two mouthfuls wouldn't be that dangerous as long as it goes down to your stomach and stays there or keeps going".
[src:gasoline/gasoline] CDC's Agency for Toxic Substances and Disease Registry says not to induce vomiting, lavage, or administer activated charcoal.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Inhaled (huffed) gasoline vapor is a common intoxicant.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Users concentrate and inhale gasoline vapor in a manner not intended by the manufacturer to produce euphoria and intoxication.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Gasoline inhalation has become epidemic in some poorer communities and indigenous groups in Australia, Canada, New Zealand, and some Pacific Islands.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The practice is thought to cause severe organ damage, along with other effects such as intellectual disability and various cancers.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] In Canada, Native children in the isolated Northern Labrador community of Davis Inlet were the focus of national concern in 1993, when many were found to be sniffing gasoline.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The Canadian and provincial Newfoundland and Labrador governments intervened on several occasions, sending many children away for treatment.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Despite being moved to the new community of Natuashish in 2002, serious inhalant abuse problems have continued.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Similar problems were reported in Sheshatshiu in 2000 and also in Pikangikum First Nation.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] In 2012, the issue once again made the news media in Canada.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Australia has long faced a petrol (gasoline) sniffing problem in isolated and impoverished aboriginal communities.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Chronic, heavy petrol sniffing appears to occur among remote, impoverished indigenous communities, where the ready accessibility of petrol has helped to make it a common substance for abuse.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] In Australia, petrol sniffing now occurs widely throughout remote Aboriginal communities in the Northern Territory, Western Australia, northern parts of South Australia, and Queensland.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The number of people sniffing petrol goes up and down over time as young people experiment or sniff occasionally.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] "Boss", or chronic, sniffers may move in and out of communities; they are often responsible for encouraging young people to take it up.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] In 2005, the Government of Australia and BP Australia began the usage of Opal fuel in remote areas prone to petrol sniffing.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Opal is a non-sniffable fuel, which is much less likely to cause a high, and has made a difference in some indigenous communities.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Gasoline is flammable with its lowest flash point from −38 °C (−36 °F) to −43 °C (−45 °F).
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Gasoline has a lower explosive limit of 1.4 percent by volume and an upper explosive limit of 7.6 percent.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] If the concentration is below 1.4 percent, the air-gasoline mixture is too lean and does not ignite.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] If the concentration is above 7.6 percent, the mixture is too rich and also does not ignite.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] However, gasoline vapor rapidly mixes and spreads with air, making unconstrained gasoline quickly flammable.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The exhaust gas generated by burning gasoline is harmful to both the environment and to human health.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] After CO is inhaled into the human body, it readily combines with haemoglobin in the blood, and its affinity is 300 times that of oxygen.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Therefore, the haemoglobin in the lungs combines with CO instead of oxygen, causing the human body to be hypoxic, causing headaches, dizziness, vomiting, and other poisoning symptoms.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Hydrocarbons only affect the human body when their concentration is quite high, and their toxicity level depends on the chemical composition.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The hydrocarbons produced by incomplete combustion include alkanes, aromatics, and aldehydes.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] If the concentration of benzene exceeds 40 ppm, it can cause leukaemia, and xylene can cause headache, dizziness, nausea, and vomiting.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Human exposure to large amounts of aldehydes can cause eye irritation, nausea, and dizziness.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] In addition to carcinogenic effects, long-term exposure can cause damage to the skin, liver, kidneys, and cataracts.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] After NOx enters the alveoli, it has a severe stimulating effect on the lung tissue.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] It can irritate the conjunctiva of the eyes, cause tearing, and cause pink eyes.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] It also has a stimulating effect on the nose, pharynx, throat, and other organs.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] It can cause acute wheezing, breathing difficulties, red eyes, sore throat, and dizziness causing poisoning.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Fine particulates are also dangerous to health.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The air pollution in many large cities has changed from coal-burning pollution to "motor vehicle pollution".
[src:gasoline/gasoline] In the U.S., transportation is the largest source of carbon emissions, accounting for 30 percent of the total carbon footprint of the U.S.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Combustion of gasoline produces 2.35 kilograms per liter (19.6 lb/U.S. gal) of carbon dioxide, a greenhouse gas.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Unburnt gasoline and evaporation from the tank, when in the atmosphere, react in sunlight to produce photochemical smog.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Vapor pressure initially rises with some addition of ethanol to gasoline, but the increase is greatest at 10 percent by volume.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] At higher concentrations of ethanol above 10 percent, the vapor pressure of the blend starts to decrease.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] At a 10 percent ethanol by volume, the rise in vapor pressure may potentially increase the problem of photochemical smog.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] This rise in vapor pressure could be mitigated by increasing or decreasing the percentage of ethanol in the gasoline mixture.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The chief risks of such leaks come not from vehicles, but gasoline delivery truck accidents and leaks from storage tanks.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Because of this risk, most (underground) storage tanks now have extensive measures in place to detect and prevent any such leaks, such as monitoring systems (Veeder-Root, Franklin Fueling).
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Production of gasoline consumes 1.5 liters per kilometer (0.63 U.S. gal/mi) of water by driven distance.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Gasoline use causes a variety of deleterious effects to the human population and to the climate generally.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The costs imposed on society and the planet are estimated to be $3.80 per gallon of gasoline, in addition to the price paid at the pump by the user.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The damage to the health and climate caused by a gasoline-powered vehicle greatly exceeds that caused by electric vehicles.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Gasoline can be released into the environment as an uncombusted liquid fuel, as a flammable liquid, or as a vapor by way of leakages occurring during its production, handling, transport and delivery.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Gasoline contains known carcinogens, and gasoline exhaust is a health risk.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Gasoline is often used as a recreational inhalant and can be harmful or fatal when used in such a manner.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] When burned, one liter (0.26 U.S. gal) of gasoline emits about 2.3 kilograms (5.1 lb) of CO2, a greenhouse gas, contributing to human-caused climate change.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Oil products, including gasoline, were responsible for about 32% of CO2 emissions worldwide in 2021.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] About 2.353 kilograms per liter (19.64 lb/U.S. gal) of carbon dioxide (CO2) are produced from burning gasoline that does not contain ethanol.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Most of the retail gasoline now sold in the U.S. contains about 10 percent fuel ethanol (or E10) by volume.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Burning E10 produces about 2.119 kilograms per liter (17.68 lb/U.S. gal) of CO2 that is emitted from the fossil fuel content.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] If the CO2 emissions from ethanol combustion are considered, then about 2.271 kilograms per liter (18.95 lb/U.S. gal) of CO2 are produced when E10 is combusted.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Worldwide 7 litres of gasoline are burnt for every 100 km driven by cars and vans.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Gasoline enters the environment through the soil, groundwater, surface water, and air.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Therefore, humans may be exposed to gasoline through methods such as breathing, eating, and skin contact.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] For example, using gasoline-filled equipment, such as lawnmowers, drinking gasoline-contaminated water close to gasoline spills or leaks to the soil, working at a gasoline station, inhaling gasoline volatile gas when refuelling at a gasoline station is the easiest way to be exposed to gasoline.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The International Energy Agency said in 2021 that "road fuels should be taxed at a rate that reflects their impact on people's health and the climate".
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Countries in Europe impose substantially higher taxes on fuels such as gasoline when compared to the U.S.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The price of gasoline in Europe is typically higher than that in the U.S. due to this difference.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] In the United States, retail gasoline prices include taxes, unlike most consumer goods, which are commonly advertised before sales taxes are added.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The retail price of gasoline is mainly determined by the cost of crude oil, taxes, refining costs and profits, and distribution and marketing costs.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] In 2025, the national annual average price of regular-grade gasoline was $0.82 per liter ($3.10/U.S. gal); the EIA estimated that crude oil accounted for about 51% of the retail price, with taxes, refining, and distribution and marketing accounting for the remainder.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Gasoline prices have fluctuated substantially over time.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] They reached about $1.09 per liter ($4.11/U.S. gal) in mid-2008 before falling during the late-2000s recession.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] After another period of high prices in the early 2010s, prices fell in 2020 during the COVID-19 pandemic and later rose to a nominal high of about $1.3 per liter ($5/U.S. gal) in mid-2022.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Federal, state, and local taxes contribute to gasoline prices.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] As of January 2026, the federal tax on motor gasoline was $0.049 per liter ($0.184/U.S. gal), including the federal excise tax and the Leaking Underground Storage Tank fee, while state taxes and fees averaged $0.0886 per liter ($0.3355/U.S. gal).
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The federal motor fuel excise tax is deposited into the Highway Trust Fund.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Gasoline is sold in regular, midgrade, and premium grades, which differ primarily by octane rating.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Higher-octane gasoline is more resistant to engine knocking and is typically more expensive.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] In 2025, the national annual average price of premium-grade gasoline was about $0.25 per liter ($0.93/U.S. gal) higher than regular-grade gasoline.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] The price of gasoline varies seasonally.
[src:gasoline/gasoline] Summer-grade gasoline has lower vapor pressure to reduce evaporation, ozone formation, and smog in warm weather, while winter-grade gasoline has higher vapor pressure to improve cold-weather starting.
